e in SA|last=Goldstuck|first=Arthur|work=Gadget|date=December 18, 2019|access-date=December 20, 2019}}</ref> Lediga and Tebogo Malope will both direct the entirety of the first season.<ref name=\"Casting2\"/> Diprente Films will be involved in the production of the series.<ref name=\"SeriesOrder\"/> The first season is set to be released on February 28, 2020.<ref name=\"AnnouncementTeaserTrailer\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.glamafrica.com/queen-sono/|title=Queen is coming: Queen Sono premieres February 28th, 2020|last=Winifred|first=Chisom|work=Glam Africa|date=December 10, 2019|access-date=December 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\nAlongside the series order announcement, it was confirmed that [[Pearl Thusi]] would star in the lead role.<ref name=\"FirstNetflixAfricanOriginalSeries\">{{Cite web|url=https://media.netflix.com/en/press-releases/first-netflix-original-series-in-africa-to-star-south-african-actress-pearl-thusi|title=First Netflix Original Series in Africa to star South African actress Pearl Thusi|website=Netflix Media Center|date=December 12, 2018|accessdate=February 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/netflix-orders-first-african-original-series-queen-sono-1167858|title=Netflix Orders First African Original Series 'Queen Sono'|last=Richford|first=Rhonda|publisher=Hollywood Reporter|date=December 12, 2018|accessdate=February 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/sunday-times/lifestyle/2019-12-15-i-hope-people-enjoy-watching-a-female-badass-in-action-says-pearl-thusi-of-queen-sono/|title=I hope people enjoy watching a 'female badass' in action, says Pearl Thusi of 'Queen Sono'|last=Smith|first=Tymon|work=TimesLive|date=December 15, 2019|access-date=January 31, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/tv/2020/02/26/netflix-queen-sono-pearl-thusi-highlights/|title=Why you should watch Queen Sono, Netflix's first African original series|last=Yohannes|first=Alamin|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=February 26, 2020|access-date=February 27, 2020}}</ref> On June 11, 2019, it was announced [[Vuyo Dabula]], Sechaba Morojele, Chi Mhende, Loyiso Madinga, Rob Van Vuuren, Kate Liquorish, Khathu Ramabulana, Enhle Maphumulo, [[Abigail Kubeka]], Connie Chiume, Otto Nobelaand James Ngcobo had joined the cast.<ref name=\"Casting2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.okayafrica.com/production-for-queen-sono-netflix-first-african-original-series-is-underway/|title=Production for 'Queen Sono,' Netflix's First African Original Series, Is Underway|last=Isama|first=Antoinette|work=OkayAfrica|date=June 11, 2019|accessdate=June 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nPrincipal photography for the first season was originally scheduled to commence in April 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.biznews.com/good-hope-project/2019/02/12/movie-matwetwe-director-kagiso-lediga|title=Hitting highs with movie hit Matwetwe: Meet director Kagiso Lediga|last=van Zyl|first=Gareth|publisher=BizNews|date=February 12, 2019|accessdate=February 12, 2019}}</ref> Filming for the first season took place [[On location filming|on location]] in [[Johannesburg]], [[South Africa]], [[Lagos]], [[Nigeria]], [[Kenya]] and [[Zanzibar]], [[Tanzania]] from June 2019 to August 2019.<ref name=\"Casting2\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B00KHTkgasj/|title=And just like that, season 1 is in the can. It done. It's over.|date=August 6, 2019|access-date=August 17, 2019|first1=Pearl|last1=Thusi|website=[[Instagram]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.channel24.co.za/TV/News/first-look-at-pearl-thusi-and-cast-in-netflix-african-original-queen-sono-20191118-2|title=First look at Pearl Thusi and cast in Netflix African original 'Queen Sono'|last=Engelbrecht|first=Leandra|work=Channel 24|date=November 18, 2019|access-date=November 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n\nOn December 10, 2019, an announcement teaser trailer for the series was released by Netflix.<ref name=\"AnnouncementTeaserTrailer\">{{cite web|url=https://za.ign.com/queen-sono/139918/news/queen-sono-first-teaser-and-release-date-announced|title=Queen Sono: First Teaser and Release Date Announced|last=Kriel|first=Zaid|work=IGN Africa|date=December 10, 2019|access-date=December 11, 2019}}</ref> On January 30, 2020, Netflix released the official trailer for the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://za.ign.com/queen-sono/141290/trailer/queen-sono-official-trailer-netflix|title=Full Trailer for Netflix's Queen Sono|work=IGN Africa|date=January 30, 2020|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2020/01/queen-sono-trailer-netflix-african-series-watch-1202207278/|title=\u2018Queen Sono\u2019 Trailer: Netflix\u2019s First African Original Series Stars a Jason Bourne-Like Heroine|last=Obenson|first=Tambay|work=IndieWire|date=January 30, 2020|access-date=January 31, 2020}}</ref>\n==Reception==\nThe first season received positive reviews upon its release. The [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reported a 90% approval rating with an average rating of 7/10 based on 10 reviews. The website's critical consensus reads, \"''Queen Sono's'' twisty, taut thrills are matched with epic action sequences and soapy delights, making Netflix's first South African series a smashing good time.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/queen_sono/s01/|title=Queen Sono: Season 1 (2020)|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|access-date=February 28, 2020}}</ref> [[Metacritic]], which uses a weighted average, assigned the first season a score of 70 out of 100 based on 5 critics, indicating \"generally favorable\" reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/queen-sono|title=''Queen Sono'': Season 1|website=[[Metacritic]]|access-date=February 28, 2020}}</ref> Queen Sono has been adjudged one of the Best Bingeworthy TV Shows on Netflix<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.unorthodoxreviews.com/11-bingeworthy-tv-shows-on-netflix/|title=11 Amazing Bingeworthy TV Shows on Netflix|publisher=Unorthodox Reviews|access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Netflix title|81035137}}\n*{{IMDb title|9426290}}\n\n{{Netflix original series}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Queen Sono (2020 TV Series)}}\n\n[[Category:2020s South African television series debuts]]\n[[Category:South African drama television series]]\n[[Category:2020s crime drama television series]]\n[[Category:Netflix original programming]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Thriller television series]]\n[[Category:Serial drama television series]]\n[[Category:Espionage television series]]\n[[Category:Spy thriller television series]]\n[[Category:Suspense television series]]\n[[Category:Posttraumatic stress disorder in fiction]]\n[[Category: Television shows set in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Johannesburg, South Africa]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Kenya]]\n[[Category:Television shows filmed in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Television shows filmed in Kenya]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Lagos]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Africa]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|South African Netflix drama}}\n\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = Queen Sono\n| image                    = File:Poster_for_Netflix_series_Queen_Sono.png\n| caption                  = Promotional release poster\n| genre                    = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Crime drama]]\n* [[Action (fiction)|Action]]\n* [[Thriller (genre)|Thriller]]\n}}\n| creator                  = [[Kagiso Lediga]]\n| starring                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Pearl Thusi]]\n* [[Vuyo Dabula]] \n* Sechaba Morojele\n* Chi Mhende\n* Loyiso Madinga\n* Rob Van Vuuren\n* Kate Liquorish\n* Khathu Ramabulana\n* Enhle Maphumulo\n* [[Abigail Kubeka]]\n* Connie Chiume\n* Otto Nobela\n* James Ngcobo\n}}\n| writer                   = {{Plainlist|\n* Kagiso Lediga\n* Karabo Lediga\n* Camilo Saloojee\n* Christopher Steenkamp \n* Muzi Dlamini\n}}\n| director                 = {{Plainlist|\n* Kagiso Lediga \n* Tebogo Malope\n}}\n| composer                 = Zethu Mashika\n| theme_music_composer     = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Sauti Sol]]\n* [[Sho Madjozi]]\n* Black Motion\n}}\n| opentheme                = Disco Matanga\n| country                  = South Africa, Congo, Nigeria,  Zimbabwe\n| language                 = {{Plainlist|\n* English\n* French \n* Russian\n* Swahili\n* Afrikaans\n* Xhosa\n* Zulu\n* Pretoria Sotho\n* Shona\n* Yoruba\n* Xitsonga\n}}\n| num_seasons              = 1\n| num_episodes             = 6\n| list_episodes            = #Episodes\n| executive_producer       = {{Plainlist|\n* Kagiso Lediga\n* Tamsin Andersson\n}}\n| producer                 = \n| cinematography           = Motheo Moeng\n| camera                   = [[Single-camera]]\n| picture_format           = [[4K resolution|4K]] ([[16:9]] [[Ultra-high-definition television|UHDTV]])\n| audio_format             = [[Dolby Digital]]\n| editor                   = {{Plainlist|\n* Melissa Parry S.A.G.E.\n* Gugu Sibandze S.A.G.E. \n* Khulekani Zondi \n}}\n| runtime                  = 32\u201347 min\n| company                  = {{nowrap|Diprente Films}}\n| network                  = [[Netflix]]\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|2020|2|28}}\n| last_aired               = {{End date|present}}\n| website                  = https://www.netflix.com/title/81035137\n}}\n'''''Queen Sono''''' is a South African [[Crime film|crime drama]] [[web television]] series created by [[Kagiso Lediga]] that premiered on [[Netflix]] on February 28, 2020.<ref name=\"AnnouncementTeaserTrailer\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://za.ign.com/queen-sono/139918/news/queen-sono-first-teaser-and-release-date-announced|title=Queen Sono: First Teaser and Release Date Announced|last=Kriel|first=Zaid|work=IGN Africa|date=December 10, 2019|access-date=December 11, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Casting2\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://za.ign.com/queen-sono/139614/feature/queen-sono-netflix-takes-the-hero-shot|title=Queen Sono: Netflix Takes the Hero Shot|last=Kriel|first=Zaid|work=IGN Africa|date=December 2, 2019|access-date=December 3, 2019}}</ref> The series stars [[Pearl Thusi]], [[Vuyo Dabula]], Sechaba Morojele, Chi Mhende, Loyiso Madinga, Rob Van Vuuren, Kate Liquorish, Khathu Ramabulana, Enhle Maphumulo, [[Abigail Kubeka]], Connie Chiume, Otto Nobela and James Ngcobo.<ref name=\"Casting2\"/> It is [[Netflix]]'s first African original series.<ref name=\"FirstNetflixAfricanOriginalSeries\"/>{{efn|''Queen Sono'' was the first South African series commissioned by Netflix, but ''[[Shadow (South African TV series)|Shadow]]'' was streamed first on the service since ''Queen Sono'' later premiered on February 28, 2020.}}\n\n==Synopsis==\n''Queen Sono'' follows the story of a secret South African clandestine agent who tackles criminal operations while dealing with crises in her personal life.<ref name=\"Info\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/tv/news/netflix-orders-queen-sono-first-african-original-series-1203085465/|title=Netflix Orders \u2018Queen Sono,\u2019 Its First African Original Series|first=Christopher|last=Vourlias|date=December 10, 2018|publisher=Variety|accessdate=December 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Cast and characters==\n===Main===\n* [[Pearl Thusi]] as Queen Sono, a [[field agent|field operative]] of the Special Operations Group (SOG) and daughter of Safiya Sono, a deceased anti-apartheid revolutionary leader and freedom fighter\n* [[Vuyo Dabula]] as Shandu Johnson Magwaza, an ex-SOG agent and Ekaterina's second in command\n* Sechaba Morojele as Dr. Sidwell Isaacs, Chief Director of the SOG\n* Chi Mhende as Miri Dube, Director General of the SOG\n* Loyiso Madinga as Frederique Kazadi, a former [[hacker]] and lead field technician of the SOG\n* Rob Van Vuuren as Viljoen, a former SOG field agent, who later became an analyst after suffering a permanent impairment injury from a past covert operation \n* Kate Liquorish as Ekaterina Gromova, a high level security contractor and primary owner of the private military company Superior Solutions, as well as a Russian heiress to the Gromova crime family\n* Khathu Ramabulana as William Chakela, Queen's childhood friend and therapist\n* Enhle Maphumulo as Nova, William's girlfriend and a consultant at the [[World Bank]]\n* [[Abigail Kubeka]] as Mazet, Queen's paternal grandmother\n* Connie Chiume as Nana, Miri's mother and a key political advisor \n* Otto Nobela as Bula Bule, one of Ekaterina's mercenaries \n* James Ngcobo as [[President of South Africa|President]] Malunga, a prominent South African political figurehead\n\n==Episodes==\n{{Episode table |total_width=80 |background=#56CCDF |overall= |title= |director= |writer= |airdate= |airdateR=<ref name=\"TFC\">{{cite web |title=Queen Sono \u2013 Listings |url=http://www.thefutoncritic.com/showatch/queen-sono/listings/ |website=[[The Futon Critic]] |accessdate=January 29, 2020}}</ref> |released=y |country=U.S. |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber   = 1\n| Title           = I Am Queen Sono\n| DirectedBy      = [[Kagiso Lediga]]\n| WrittenBy       = Kagiso Lediga\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|2|28}}\n| ShortSummary    = In Zanzibar, Queen Sono (an undercover secret agent) is tasked with obtaining data about a private arms company called Superior Solutions from one of its senior operatives. When the initial plan to hack the data fails due to signal blocking technology, Queen resorts to stealing the required intel manually and engages in a fight with law enforcement operatives after being compromised. She manages to escape using a decoy and, together with her partner Fred, travels back to South Africa to report to their seniors at the Special Operations Group (SOG). There, she learns about a new terrorist group calling themselves the Watu Wema who plan to liberate Africa. Queen later has her friend and therapist William write her a complementary psychological evaluation at the request of her boss Sid. On the anniversary of her mother Safia's assassination, Queen meets with her grandmother Mazet and the two of them visit Safia's grave where a desolate Queen refuses to talk with her mother. In Congo, the Watu Wema appear at a slave mine and kill the guards and superiors, granting freedom to the enslaved miners. Shandu, Queen's ex and a former SOG agent is revealed as the leader of the terrorist group. Queen later receives information that her mother's killer is going to be released on parole due to age and frailty. She later visits him in prison and forces him to tell her what happened on the day of Safia's assassination. His story about shooting Safia as she sat on a park bench is revealed to be a lie when Queen recalls the shooter being in a moving car when she was five years old; revealing that Queen was there when her mother was shot.\n| LineColor       = 56CCDF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 2\n| Title           = Dying Is Sore\n| DirectedBy      = Kagiso Lediga\n| WrittenBy       = Camilo Saloojee\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|2|28}}\n| ShortSummary    = <!-- Episode summaries must be expressed in your own words. Do NOT submit content you find from another web site as it is plagiarism and likely a copyright violation, which Wikipedia cannot accept and will be removed or reverted. Superficially modifying copyrighted content or closely paraphrasing it, even if the source is cited, still constitutes a copyright violation. Summaries should be about 100 to 200 words in length, per WP:TVPLOT, and those substantially less than 100 words are most likely to be scrutinized for possible copyright violation. -->\n| LineColor       = 56CCDF\n}}\n{{Episode list\n| EpisodeNumber   = 3\n| Title           = The Devil's Toys\n| DirectedBy      = Tebogo Malope\n| WrittenBy       = Muzi Dlamini & Karabo Lediga\n| OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2020|2|28}}\n| ShortSummary    