l/kagiso-lediga-speaks-about-queen-sono-%E2%80%93-africas-first-netflix-original-series/ar-BBTosOO|title=Kagiso Lediga speaks about Queen Sono \u2013 Africa\u2019s First Netflix Original Series|last=Buso|first=Oyama|publisher=MSN Entertainment|date=February 10, 2019|accessdate=February 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://gadget.co.za/behind-the-scenes-of-netflix-sas-queen-sono/|title=Behind the scenes of Netflix SA\u2019s Queen Sono|last=Turner|first=Bryan|work=Gadget|date=November 19, 2019|access-date=November 19, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://gadget.co.za/netflix-goes-into-overdrive/|title=Netflix goes into overdrive in SA|last=Goldstuck|first=Arthur|work=Gadget|date=December 18, 2019|access-date=December 20, 2019}}</ref> Lediga and Tebogo Malope will both direct the entirety of the first season.<ref name=\"Casting2\"/> Diprente Films will be involved in the production of the series.<ref name=\"SeriesOrder\"/> The first season is set to be released on February 28, 2020.<ref name=\"AnnouncementTeaserTrailer\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.glamafrica.com/queen-sono/|title=Queen is coming: Queen Sono premieres February 28th, 2020|last=Winifred|first=Chisom|work=Glam Africa|date=December 10, 2019|access-date=December 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\nAlongside the series order announcement, it was confirmed that [[Pearl Thusi]] would star in the lead role.<ref name=\"FirstNetflixAfricanOriginalSeries\">{{Cite web|url=https://media.netflix.com/en/press-releases/first-netflix-original-series-in-africa-to-star-south-african-actress-pearl-thusi|title=First Netflix Original Series in Africa to star South African actress Pearl Thusi|website=Netflix Media Center|date=December 12, 2018|accessdate=February 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/netflix-orders-first-african-original-series-queen-sono-1167858|title=Netflix Orders First African Original Series 'Queen Sono'|last=Richford|first=Rhonda|publisher=Hollywood Reporter|date=December 12, 2018|accessdate=February 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.timeslive.co.za/sunday-times/lifestyle/2019-12-15-i-hope-people-enjoy-watching-a-female-badass-in-action-says-pearl-thusi-of-queen-sono/|title=I hope people enjoy watching a 'female badass' in action, says Pearl Thusi of 'Queen Sono'|last=Smith|first=Tymon|work=TimesLive|date=December 15, 2019|access-date=January 31, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/tv/2020/02/26/netflix-queen-sono-pearl-thusi-highlights/|title=Why you should watch Queen Sono, Netflix's first African original series|last=Yohannes|first=Alamin|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=February 26, 2020|access-date=February 27, 2020}}</ref> On June 11, 2019, it was announced [[Vuyo Dabula]], Sechaba Morojele, Chi Mhende, Loyiso Madinga, Rob Van Vuuren, Kate Liquorish, Khathu Ramabulana, Enhle Maphumulo, [[Abigail Kubeka]], Connie Chiume, Otto Nobelaand James Ngcobo had joined the cast.<ref name=\"Casting2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.okayafrica.com/production-for-queen-sono-netflix-first-african-original-series-is-underway/|title=Production for 'Queen Sono,' Netflix's First African Original Series, Is Underway|last=Isama|first=Antoinette|work=OkayAfrica|date=June 11, 2019|accessdate=June 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Filming===\nPrincipal photography for the first season was originally scheduled to commence in April 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.biznews.com/good-hope-project/2019/02/12/movie-matwetwe-director-kagiso-lediga|title=Hitting highs with movie hit Matwetwe: Meet director Kagiso Lediga|last=van Zyl|first=Gareth|publisher=BizNews|date=February 12, 2019|accessdate=February 12, 2019}}</ref> Filming for the first season took place [[On location filming|on location]] in [[Johannesburg]], [[South Africa]], [[Lagos]], [[Nigeria]], [[Kenya]] and [[Zanzibar]], [[Tanzania]] from June 2019 to August 2019.<ref name=\"Casting2\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B00KHTkgasj/|title=And just like that, season 1 is in the can. It done. It's over.|date=August 6, 2019|access-date=August 17, 2019|first1=Pearl|last1=Thusi|website=[[Instagram]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.channel24.co.za/TV/News/first-look-at-pearl-thusi-and-cast-in-netflix-african-original-queen-sono-20191118-2|title=First look at Pearl Thusi and cast in Netflix African original 'Queen Sono'|last=Engelbrecht|first=Leandra|work=Channel 24|date=November 18, 2019|access-date=November 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Release==\n\nOn December 10, 2019, an announcement teaser trailer for the series was released by Netflix.<ref name=\"AnnouncementTeaserTrailer\">{{cite web|url=https://za.ign.com/queen-sono/139918/news/queen-sono-first-teaser-and-release-date-announced|title=Queen Sono: First Teaser and Release Date Announced|last=Kriel|first=Zaid|work=IGN Africa|date=December 10, 2019|access-date=December 11, 2019}}</ref> On January 30, 2020, Netflix released the official trailer for the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://za.ign.com/queen-sono/141290/trailer/queen-sono-official-trailer-netflix|title=Full Trailer for Netflix's Queen Sono|work=IGN Africa|date=January 30, 2020|access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2020/01/queen-sono-trailer-netflix-african-series-watch-1202207278/|title=\u2018Queen Sono\u2019 Trailer: Netflix\u2019s First African Original Series Stars a Jason Bourne-Like Heroine|last=Obenson|first=Tambay|work=IndieWire|date=January 30, 2020|access-date=January 31, 2020}}</ref>\n==Reception==\nThe first season received positive reviews upon its release. The [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]] reported a 90% approval rating with an average rating of 7/10 based on 10 reviews. The website's critical consensus reads, \"''Queen Sono's'' twisty, taut thrills are matched with epic action sequences and soapy delights, making Netflix's first South African series a smashing good time.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/tv/queen_sono/s01/|title=Queen Sono: Season 1 (2020)|publisher=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|access-date=February 28, 2020}}</ref> [[Metacritic]], which uses a weighted average, assigned the first season a score of 70 out of 100 based on 5 critics, indicating \"generally favorable\" reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/tv/queen-sono|title=''Queen Sono'': Season 1|website=[[Metacritic]]|access-date=February 28, 2020}}</ref> Queen Sono has been adjudged one of the Best Bingeworthy TV Shows on Netflix<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.unorthodoxreviews.com/11-bingeworthy-tv-shows-on-netflix/|title=11 Amazing Bingeworthy TV Shows on Netflix|publisher=Unorthodox Reviews|access-date=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Netflix title|81035137}}\n*{{IMDb title|9426290}}\n\n{{Netflix original series}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Queen Sono (2020 TV Series)}}\n\n[[Category:2020s South African television series debuts]]\n[[Category:South African drama television series]]\n[[Category:2020s crime drama television series]]\n[[Category:Netflix original programming]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Thriller television series]]\n[[Category:Serial drama television series]]\n[[Category:Espionage television series]]\n[[Category:Spy thriller television series]]\n[[Category:Suspense television series]]\n[[Category:Posttraumatic stress disorder in fiction]]\n[[Category: Television shows set in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Johannesburg, South Africa]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Kenya]]\n[[Category:Television shows filmed in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Television shows filmed in Kenya]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Nigeria]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Lagos]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Africa]]\n", "name_user": "Lutfi.djibran", "label": "safe", "comment": "just adding my version of episode 2 story plot of Queen Sono", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Queen_Sono"}
{"title_page": "Secretomotor", "text_new": "{{Wiktionary}}\n\n'''Secretomotor''' refers to the capacity of a structure (often a [[nerve]]) to induce a [[gland]] to secrete a substance (usually [[mucus]] or [[serous fluid]]). More specifically, '''Secretomotor''' refers to the excitable [[motor neuron]]s of enteric nervous system in [[Submucosa|mucosal ganglia]] innervating the mucosa of the small and large intestines.<ref name=\"Caplan 2014 p. \"/><ref name=\"Said 2018 p. \"/><ref name=\"Wood 2012 pp. 629\u2013669\">{{cite book | last=Wood | first=Jackie D. | title=Physiology of the Gastrointestinal Tract | chapter=Cellular Neurophysiology of Enteric Neurons | publisher=Elsevier | year=2012 | isbn=978-0-12-382026-6 | doi=10.1016/b978-0-12-382026-6.00021-x | pages=629\u2013669}}</ref>\n\n==Physiology==\nWhether secretomotor is excitatory or inhibitory depends on the mediation of [[sympathetic nervous system]]'s [[postganglionic neurons]], [[enteric nervous system]], and [[paracrine signaling]]s from nonneural cell types in the mucosa and submucosa such as [[enterochromaffin cell]]s and [[inflammatory cell]]s.<ref name=\"Said 2018 p. \"/>\n\nWhenever secretomotor neurons get [[Excitable membrane|excited]], they release [[vasoactive intestinal peptide]] (VIP) and [[acetylcholine]] as its [[neurotransmitter]]s to communicate while the role of acetylcholine that binds to [[cholinergic secretomotor neurons]] is secondary to VIP during this procedure.{{noteTag|name= |1= Cholinergic (ChAT) and VIP-containing neurons make up a third and one half of the overall neurons, respectively.<ref name=\"Cooke Christofi 2006 pp. 737\u2013762\">{{cite book | last=Cooke | first=Helen Joan | last2=Christofi | first2=Fedias Leontiou | title=Physiology of the Gastrointestinal Tract | chapter=Enteric Neural Regulation of Mucosal Secretion | publisher=Elsevier | year=2006 | isbn=978-0-12-088394-3 | doi=10.1016/b978-012088394-3/50030-1 | pages=737\u2013762}}</ref> <br/> In that, there are three types of [[Choline acetyltransferase]] (ChAT) neurons in accordance with the chemical coding as follows: \n#S/type 1 cholinergic neurons coded as ChAT/[[calretinin]] ([[CALRET]]) are vasomotor and innervate the glands and arterioles;\n#ChAT [[neuropeptide Y]] (NPY) secretomotor neurons;\n#ChAT\u2212/secretomotor neurons lacking these markers; <br/><ref name=\"Cooke Christofi 2006 pp. 737\u2013762\"/>}} \n\nIt is the release of acetylcholine triggering the release of [[nitric oxide]] from the endothelium that dilates the blood vessel and, thereafter, increases blood flow activating secretions of [[serous fluid]] made out of [[water]],<ref name=\"Wood 2007 pp. 1313\u20131332\">{{cite journal | last=Wood | first=Jackie D | title=Neuropathophysiology of functional gastrointestinal disorders | journal=World Journal of Gastroenterology | volume=13 | issue=9 | date=2007-03-07 | doi=10.3748/wjg.v13.i9.1313 | pages=1313\u20131332 | url=https://www.wjgnet.com/1007-9327/full/v13/i9/1313.htm | access-date=2020-02-13}}</ref> [[NaCl]], [[bicarbonate]], and [[mucus]] into [[gut lumen]] from the [[intestinal gland]]. <ref name=\"Said 2018 p. \">{{cite book | last=Said | first=Hamid | title=Physiology of the gastrointestinal tract | publisher=Academic Press, an imprint of Elsevier | publication-place=London | year=2018 | isbn=978-0-12-809954-4 | oclc=1028731517 | page=}}</ref><ref name=\"Caplan 2014 p. \">{{cite book | last=Caplan | first=Michael | title=Reference module in biomedical research | publisher=Elsevier | publication-place=Place of publication not identified | year=2014 | isbn=978-0-12-801238-3 | oclc=902812782 | page=}}</ref>\n\n[[Norepinephrine]] released from sympathetic postganglionic neurons' terminals acts at [[alpha-2A adrenergic receptor]]s which [[Hyperpolarization_(biology)|hyperpolarize]]s the [[membrane potential]] of secretomotor neurons, decreasing the firing and thus the release of acetylcholine liable for stimulating intestinal gland's secretion. <ref name=\"Johnson 2006 p. \">{{cite book | last=Johnson | first=Leonard | title=Physiology of the gastrointestinal tract | publisher=Elsevier Academic Press | publication-place=Amsterdam Boston | year=2006 | isbn=978-0-12-088394-3 | oclc=162569660 | page=}}</ref> This explains the reason for why whenever sympathetic nervous system is in excitatory state, gastrointestinal becomes less watery. This is because the sympathetic nervous system tends to divert blood from the splanchnic to the systemic circulation.<ref name=\"Johnson 2006 p. \"/>\n\n===Neurotransmitters, endocrine, or exocrine that excites secretomotor receptor===\n*[[Acetylcholine]] (acting at nicotinic receptors, and the muscarinic M1 subtype), [[Adenosine triphosphate|ATP]] (acting at the P2Y1 receptor subtype), [[vasoactive intestinal peptide]], [[substance P]] (acting at NK1 and/or NK3 receptor subtypes), [[serotonin]] (acting at 5-HT3 and perhaps 5-HT2 receptor subtypes), and [[prostaglandin]]. <ref name=\"Johnson 2006 p. \"/><ref name=\"Wood 2012 pp. 629\u2013669\"/><ref name=\"Cooke Christofi 2006 pp. 737\u2013762\"/>\n*Pro-inflammatory factors that trigger histamine release.<ref name=\"Wood 2012 pp. 629\u2013669\"/>\n\n===Neurotransmitters, endocrine, or exocrine that hyperpolarizes secretomotor receptor===\n*[[Somatostatin]], [[norepinephrine]].<ref name=\"Wood 2012 pp. 629\u2013669\">{{cite book | last=Wood | first=Jackie D. | title=Physiology of the Gastrointestinal Tract | chapter=Cellular Neurophysiology of Enteric Neurons | publisher=Elsevier | year=2012 | isbn=978-0-12-382026-6 | doi=10.1016/b978-0-12-382026-6.00021-x | pages=629\u2013669}}</ref>\n\n==Pathophysiology==\n\nThe inherent nature of secretomotor neurons making it directly connected with '''neurogenic secretory diarrhea''' and '''neurogenic constipation'''. <ref name=\"Johnson 2006 p. \"/>\n\nGenerally speaking, excitatory secretomotor is liable for neurogenic secretory diarrhea; hyperpolarized secretomotor is liable for neurogenic constipation.<ref name=\"Johnson 2006 p. \"/>\n\n[[Antidiarrhoeal]] such as  [[opiate]]s, [[clonidine]], and [[somatostatin]] analogs are associated with drier and thus harder stools.<ref name=\"Johnson 2006 p. \"/>\n\nAcetylcholine, vasoactive intestinal peptide (VIP), [[serotonin]], and [[histamine]] are associated with more watery stools.<ref name=\"Johnson 2006 p. \"/>\n\nNorepinephrine release inhibition results in the removal of the sympathetic braking action on the neurons leading to overstimulation of secretomotor neurons. <ref name=\"Johnson 2006 p. \"/>\n\nSignificant inhibitions of [[enzymatic degradation]], serotonin's movement into the blood and binding to blood platelets, or [[serotonin transporter|serotonin reuptake transporter]] (SERT) leads to accumulation of [[5-HT]] that pooled around secretomotor neurons.<ref name=\"Wood 2012 pp. 629\u2013669\"/>\n\n[[5-HT3 antagonist]]'s proven efficacy in the treatment of diarrhea in the women with [[irritable bowel syndrome]] suggests that overstimulation of secretomotor neurons by serotonin from the enterochromaffin could be a significant cause.<ref name=\"Wood 2006 pp. 629\u2013663\">{{cite book | last=Wood | first=Jackie D. | title=Physiology of the Gastrointestinal Tract | chapter=Cellular Neurophysiology of Enteric Neurons | publisher=Elsevier | year=2006 | isbn=978-0-12-088394-3 | doi=10.1016/b978-012088394-3/50026-x | pages=629\u2013663}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[IPSP]]\n*[[Gastric_acid#Regulation_of_secretion|Gastric acid \u00a7 Regulation of secretion]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{NoteFoot}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Medical terminology]]\n{{neuroanatomy-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Unreferenced|date=December 2006}}\n'''Secretomotor''' refers to the capacity of a structure (often a [[nerve]]) to induce a [[gland]] to secrete a substance (usually [[mucus]] or [[serous fluid]]).\n\nSecretomotor nerve endings are frequently contrasted with [[sensory neuron]] endings and [[motor nerve]] endings. An example of secretomotor activity can be seen with the [[lacrimal gland]], which secretes the aqueous layer of the [[tears|tear]] film. The lacrimal branch of the [[ophthalmic nerve]] (itself a branch of [[trigeminal nerve]] V1) supplies secretomotor innervation to the lacrimal gland, stimulating its secretion of the aqueous layer. However, these nerves fibers originate from the [[facial nerve]] (VII) and only travel briefly with fibers from the trigeminal nerve.\n\n[[Category:Medical terminology]]\n\n{{neuroanatomy-stub}}\n", "name_user": "At odds", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(People's health first.)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Secretomotor"}
{"title_page": "Rom\u00e9o LeBlanc", "text_new": "{{Infobox Governor General\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| honorific-suffix = {{Post-nominals|country=CAN|PC|CC|CMM|ONB|CD|size=100%}} {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|KStJ|size=100%}}\n| image            = GG-Romeo LeBlanc.jpg\n| order1           = 25th\n| office1          = Governor General of Canada\n| term_start1      = February 8, 1995\n| term_end1        = October 7, 1999\n| monarch1         = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| predecessor1     = [[Ray Hnatyshyn]]\n| successor1       = [[Adrienne Clarkson]]\n| primeminister1   = [[Jean Chr\u00e9tien]]\n| office2          = [[#External links|More...]]\n| party            = [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]]\n| birth_name       = Rom\u00e9o-Adrien LeBlanc\n| birth_date       = {{birth date|1927|12|18}}\n| birth_place      = [[Memramcook, New Brunswick|Memramcook]], [[New Brunswick]], Canada\n| death_date       = {{death date and age|2009|6|24|1927|12|18}}\n| death_place      = [[Grande-Digue, New Brunswick|Grande-Digue]], [[New Brunswick]], Canada\n| spouse           = {{unbulleted list | Lyn Carter (1966\u20131981) | [[Diana Fowler LeBlanc|Diana Fowler]] (1994\u20132009)}}\n| children         = [[Dominic LeBlanc]]<br />[[Genevieve LeBlanc]]\n| profession       = [[Politician]], [[Journalist]], [[Teacher]]\n| religion         = [[Roman Catholicism]]\n| signature        = Romeo leblanc signature.svg\n|}}\n\n'''Rom\u00e9o-Adrien LeBlanc''' {{Post-nominals|country=CAN|PC|CC|CMM|ONB|CD}} {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|KStJ}} (December 18, 1927{{spaced ndash}}June 24, 2009)<ref>{{cite web |title=State Funeral of Romeo LeBlanc |url=https://www.canada.ca/en/canadian-heritage/services/past-state-funerals-commemorations/romeo-leblanc.html |website=Government of Canada |accessdate=21 March 2019|date=2017-09-19 }}</ref> was a [[Canadians|Canadian]] journalist, politician, and statesman who served as [[Governor General of Canada]], the [[List of Governors General of Canada#Governors General of Canada, 1867\u2013present|25th]] since the [[Canadian Confederation]].\n\nLeBlanc was born and educated in [[New Brunswick]], and also studied in [[France]] prior to becoming a teacher and then a reporter for [[Radio-Canada]]. He was subsequently elected to the [[House of Commons of Canada|House of Commons]] in 1972, whereafter he served as a [[minister of the Crown]] until 1984, when he was moved to the [[Senate of Canada|Senate]] and became [[Speaker of the Senate of Canada|that chamber's Speaker]].\n\nIn 1994, he was appointed as governor general by Queen [[Elizabeth II]], on the recommendation of [[Prime Minister of Canada]] [[Jean Chr\u00e9tien]], to replace [[Ray Hnatyshyn|Ramon John Hnatyshyn]] as [[viceroy]], and he occupied the post until succeeded by [[Adrienne Clarkson]] in 1999, citing his health as the reason for his stepping down. His appointment as the Queen's representative caused some controversy, due to perceptions of political favouritism, though he was praised for raising the stature of [[Acadia]]ns and [[francophone]]s, and for returning [[Rideau Hall]] to the centre of life in Ottawa.  {{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\nOn August 8, 1974, LeBlanc was sworn into the [[Queen's Privy Council for Canada]].<ref>{{Citation|url=http://www.pco-bcp.gc.ca/index.asp?lang=eng&page=information&sub=council-conseil&doc=members-membres/chronolog-eng.htm#1971-1980|last=Privy Council Office|authorlink=Privy Council Office (Canada)|title=Information Resources> Current Chronological List of Members of the Queen's Privy Council for Canada> 1971\u20131980|publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada|date=October 30, 2008|accessdate=March 2, 2009}}</ref> He died of [[Alzheimer's disease]] on June 24, 2009, aged 81.\n\n==Youth and political career==\n[[File:1036099802 a9122606bd o.jpg|thumb|left|The rural community of [[Memramcook, New Brunswick]], where LeBlanc was born and raised]]\n\nBorn on December 18, 1927 and raised in [[Memramcook, New Brunswick]], LeBlanc obtained [[bachelor degrees]] in [[Bachelor of Arts|arts]] and [[Bachelor of Education|education]] from the [[University of St. Joseph's College|Coll\u00e8ge St-Joseph]] before studying French civilization at the [[Universit\u00e9 de Paris]]. He then moved on to teaching for nine years{{mdash}} at [[Drummond, New Brunswick|Drummond]]'s high school from 1951\u201353 and the [[New Brunswick Teachers' College]] in [[Fredericton]] from 1955-59{{mdash}} after which he obtained work between 1960-67 as a journalist with the [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]'s [[French language]] broadcaster, [[Radio-Canada]], serving in the bureaus in [[Ottawa]], the [[United Kingdom]], and the [[United States]].<ref name=LAC>{{Citation| url=http://epe.lac-bac.gc.ca/100/200/301/ic/can_digital_collections/governor/standard/pg03a.htm| last=Library and Archives Canada|title=Governor General Rom\u00e9o LeBlanc and Mrs. Diana Fowler LeBlanc|publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada|accessdate=March 2, 2009}}</ref>\n\nHis first marriage, to Joslyn \"Lyn\" Carter, with whom LeBlanc had two children (Genevieve and [[Dominic LeBlanc|Dominic]]), lasted from 1966\u201381;<ref>{{Citation|last=Martin|first=Sandra|title=He never, ever lost his roots|newspaper=The Globe and Mail|date=June 24, 2009|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/he-never-ever-lost-his-roots/article1195357|accessdate=June 24, 2009}}</ref> in 1994, he married [[Diana Fowler LeBlanc|Diana Fowler]], who also had two children from a previous marriage.<ref name=GGLeB>{{Citation|url=http://www.gg.ca/document.aspx?id=55|last=Office of the Governor General of Canada|authorlink=Governor General of Canada| title=Role and Responsibility > Former Governors General > The Right Honourable Rom\u00e9o LeBlanc|publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada|accessdate=February 1, 2010}}</ref>\n\nLeBlanc stepped into the realm of politics when he became the [[press secretary]] for successive prime ministers [[Lester B. Pearson]] and [[Pierre Trudeau]]. He then went further, winning in the [[1972 Canadian federal election|1972 federal election]] a seat in the [[House of Commons of Canada|House of Commons]] as the [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal Party]] representative for [[Beaus\u00e9jour (electoral district)|Westmorland-Kent]], paving the way for his appointment as the [[Minister of Fisheries and Oceans (Canada)|Minister of Fisheries and Oceans]] in the [[Cabinet of Canada|Cabinet]] chaired by Trudeau.\n\nLeBlanc was a key figure in Canada's imposition of a [[Exclusive Economic Zone#Canada|200-mile fishing zone]]; the establishment of a new fisheries licensing system; the widespread use of quotas and zones that protected Canadian fishermen from overexpansion and competition from [[Fishing trawler|trawlers]] owned by large companies; the owner-operator rule, requiring licence holders to operate vessels themselves; the separate-fleet rule, preventing corporations from obtaining licences for an under-65-foot fleet; and for creating an additional system of advisory committees that permitted fishermen a larger voice in fisheries management.\n\nOn one occasion, LeBlanc also persuaded Trudeau to advise the Governor General to close Canadian ports to [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] fishing vessels, a headline-grabbing diplomatic thrust that resulted in better co-operation, and forbade all foreign corporations from holding commercial fishing licences in Canada.<ref>{{Citation| last=Gough| first=Joseph| title=Managing Canada's Fisheries: From Early Days to the Year 2000| publisher=Carleton University Press| year=2007| location=Quebec| pages=289\u2013360| isbn=978-2-89448-523-1| ref=CITEREF_Gough_2007}}</ref>\n\nOn the [[Pacific Ocean|Pacific]] coast, LeBlanc oversaw the creation of the Salmonid Enhancement Program, which aimed at doubling salmon production, and quelled plans by [[Alcan]] that were deemed to threaten salmon rivers at the time.<ref>{{Harvnb| Gough| 2007| pp=368\u2013371}}</ref>\n\nLate in 1982, LeBlanc became [[Minister of Public Works (Canada)|Minister of Public Works]] for two years before being nominated by Trudeau to then Governor General [[Jeanne Sauv\u00e9]] for appointment to the [[Senate of Canada|Senate]] on June 29, 1984. He was then selected in 1993 by Prime Minister [[Jean Chr\u00e9tien]] as Governor General [[Ray Hnatyshyn]]'s appointee as [[Speaker of the Senate of Canada|that chamber's speaker]].{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\n==Governor General of Canada==\nLeBlanc's time as the Queen's viceregal representative was considered to have been low key and largely uneventful, especially in comparison to that of his successor, [[Adrienne Clarkson]].<ref name=CMNLeB>{{Citation|last=Fidelis |title=The LeBlanc Years: A Frank Assessment |journal=Canadian Monarchist News |volume=Autumn 1999 |publisher=Monarchist League of Canada |location=Toronto |year=1999 |url=http://www.monarchist.ca/cmn/1999/leblanc.htm |accessdate=March 2, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090708032551/http://www.monarchist.ca/cmn/1999/leblanc.htm |archivedate=July 8, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{Citation| last=Martin| first=Don| title=Jean is now least boring G-Gever| newspaper=National Post| date=May 28, 2009| url=https://nationalpost.com/opinion/columnists/story.html?id=f1e51d92-758b-4d2a-a554-6572d09186b1| accessdate=October 23, 2014| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://archive.is/20141023064959/http://www.nationalpost.com/opinion/columnists/story.html?id=f1e51d92-758b-4d2a-a554-6572d09186b1| archivedate=October 23, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Smith |first=David E. |year=1999 |publication-date=2007 |contribution=The Republican Option in Canada: Past and Present |editor-last=Jackson |editor-first=Michael D. |title=The Crown in Today's Federal State |periodical=Canadian Monarchist News |volume=Autumn-Winter 2007 |issue=27 |page=12 |place=Toronto-Buffalo-London |publication-place=Toronto |publisher=Monarchist League of Canada |url=http://www.monarchist.ca/cmn/2007/AutumnWinter_2007_CMN.pdf |accessdate=July 26, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090708031338/http://www.monarchist.ca/cmn/2007/AutumnWinter_2007_CMN.pdf |archivedate=July 8, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Boyce |first=Peter |year=2008 |publication-date=October 2009 |contribution=The Queen's Other Realms: The Crown and its Legacy in Australia, Canada and New Zealand |isbn=978-1-86287-700-9 |editor-last=Jackson |editor-first=Michael D. |title=The Senior Realms of the Queen |periodical=Canadian Monarchist News |volume=Autumn 2009 |issue=30 |page=10 |place=Sydney |publication-place=Toronto |publisher=Monarchist League of Canada |url=http://www.monarchist.ca/cmn/2009/Autumn_2009_CMN.pdf |accessdate=October 22, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091229100400/http://www.monarchist.ca/cmn/2009/Autumn_2009_CMN.pdf |archivedate=December 29, 2009 }}</ref> He was, however, the first governor general of [[Acadia]]n heritage, which earned praise from the Acadian community, and he was also the first from the Canadian [[maritimes]] to be appointed as viceroy.<ref name=CMNLeB />\n\n===As governor general-designate===\n[[File:SandringhamHouseWestseite.jpg|thumb|right|[[Sandringham House]], where LeBlanc met with [[Monarchy of Canada|Queen]] [[Elizabeth II]] after his appointment as Governor General-Designate]]\nIt was announced from the [[Office of the Prime Minister (Canada)|Office of the Prime Minister of Canada]] on November 22, 1994 that [[Monarchy of Canada|Queen]] [[Elizabeth II]] had approved [[Prime Minister of Canada|Prime Minister]] [[Jean Chr\u00e9tien]]'s choice of LeBlanc to succeed [[Ray Hnatyshyn]] as the Queen's representative.\n\nThereafter, LeBlanc was invited to an [[Audience (meeting)|audience]] with the Queen at [[Sandringham House]], and he was said to have been impressed and inspired by the devotion to duty on the part of both Elizabeth and [[Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother|her mother]].<ref name=CMNSun>{{Citation| author=Editorial| title=No Garish Sun| journal=Canadian Monarchist News|volume=Autumn 1999|publisher=Monarchist League of Canada|url=http://www.monarchist.ca/cmn/1999/edcom2.htm|accessdate=March 7, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090708032115/http://www.monarchist.ca/cmn/1999/edcom2.htm|archivedate=July 8, 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe commission appointing LeBlanc under the [[royal sign-manual]] and [[Great Seal of Canada]] was issued on January 16, 1995.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/databases/canada-gazette/093/001060-119.01-e.php?image_id_nbr=610383&document_id_nbr=1372&f=g&PHPSESSID=aak0t0369mpbg265s99kr6ku31|title=ARCHIVED - Item Display - A Nation's Chronicle: The Canada Gazette - Library and Archives Canada|publisher=Collectionscanada.gc.ca|accessdate=March 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe largest bout of publicity around LeBlanc and regarding his governor generalcy came immediately after the announcement of his appointment to the post: although previous governors general had worked as politicians prior to and after serving as viceroy, the recommendation of a prominent [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal Party]] politician and organiser was criticised as being little more than a [[patronage]] gift from the Prime Minister to a loyal party member.\n\nIn the [[1993 Canadian federal election|1993 federal election]], LeBlanc had been one of the chief architects of the Liberal Party's election strategy, and was a strong party loyalist. In protest, both [[Reform Party of Canada]] leader [[Preston Manning]] and [[Bloc Qu\u00e9b\u00e9cois]] leader [[Lucien Bouchard]] refused to attend LeBlanc's installation ceremony.<ref name=CMNLeB/>\n\n===In office===\nAs with each governor general, LeBlanc took on unofficial and personal mandates, choosing for himself: [[Volunteering|voluntarism]], the teaching of [[History of Canada|Canadian history]], [[Aboriginal peoples in Canada|Canada's Aboriginal peoples]], and the military. He spoke often about the generosity, tolerance, and compassion of Canadians, and admired the dignity and abilities of the common citizen.\n\nTo recognize the \"unsung heroes\" who volunteer their time and effort to help others, LeBlanc initiated in 1996 the [[Governor General's Caring Canadian Award]], and, on June 21, of the same year, was proud to issue a [[Proclamation|royal proclamation]] inaugurating [[National Aboriginal Day]] as an annual observance.<ref>{{Citation| url=http://archive.gg.ca/gg/fgg/bios/02/causes_e.asp| last=Office of the Governor General of Canada| authorlink=Governor General of Canada|title=Governor General > Former Governors General > Rom\u00e9o LeBlanc > Personal Causes of the Rt. Hon. Rom\u00e9o LeBlanc| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=March 3, 2009}}</ref>\n\nAs well, in 1996 LeBlanc formed the Governor General's Award for Excellence in Teaching Canadian History, in 1999 partnered with the [[Canada Council|Canada Council for the Arts]] to create the [[Governor General's Award#Governor General's Awards in Visual and Media Arts|Governor General's Awards in Visual and Media Arts]], oversaw the issuance of the Governor General's Canadian History Medal for the Millennium, and established the Governor General's Millennium Edition of the Map of Canada, which was taken into space in 1999 by [[Julie Payette]].<ref name=GGHigh>{{Citation|url=http://archive.gg.ca/gg/fgg/bios/02/wrap-up_e.asp|last=Office of the Governor General of Canada|authorlink=Governor General of Canada|title=Governor General> Former Governors General > Rom\u00e9o LeBlanc> Highlights of the Mandate|publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada|accessdate=February 3, 2010}}</ref>\n\nLeBlanc travelled to all parts of Canada and had a special affinity for small towns and cities, making himself particularly visible in those parts of [[Quebec]] after the [[1995 Quebec independence referendum|province's referendum on secession in 1995]]. He participated in more than 2,000 events, including the annual New Year's [[Lev\u00e9e (event)|Lev\u00e9e]], which he moved to various locations around the country, seeing the party organised at [[Ottawa]], [[Ontario]], in 1996; [[Quebec City]], [[Quebec]], in 1997; [[Winnipeg]], [[Manitoba]], in 1998; and [[St. John's, Newfoundland and Labrador]], in 1999.\n\nOver the same years, LeBlanc also had public access to Rideau Hall and [[Rideau Hall#Grounds|its grounds]] expanded and improved{{mdash}} including opening a dedicated visitors' centre in 1997{{mdash}} so that the number of visitors increased threefold to approximately 125,000 people per year.<ref name=GGHigh/> In keeping with his respect for the First Peoples of Canada, LeBlanc placed a totem pole and inukshuk prominently on the royal property.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\nAmongst numerous other official and ceremonial duties, the Governor General granted [[Royal Assent]] to amendments to [[Constitution of Canada|the constitution]] on three occasions: April 21, 1997, December 19, 1997, and January 8, 1998, and also issued the royal proclamation announcing the creation of the territory of [[Nunavut]] on April 1, 1999. LeBlanc welcomed to Rideau Hall the Queen, [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh]], and [[Charles, Prince of Wales|Prince Charles, Prince of Wales]], along with a host of foreign dignitaries such as [[President of the United States|United States president]] [[Bill Clinton]] and his wife, [[Hillary Clinton|Hillary]]; [[Hussein of Jordan|King Hussein]] and [[Queen Noor of Jordan]], and later Hussein's son, [[Abdullah II of Jordan|King Abdullah II]], and his wife [[Queen Rania of Jordan|Queen Rania]]; as well as [[President of South Africa]] [[Nelson Mandela]]; and [[President of the People's Republic of China|President of China]] [[Jiang Zemin]]. Further, he undertook eight [[state visits]], becoming the first governor general of Canada to make such trips to the [[Czech Republic]], [[India]], [[Pakistan]], the [[Ivory Coast]], [[Tanzania]], [[Mali]], and [[Morocco]].<ref name=GGHigh/>\n\n===Legacy===\nAs governor general, LeBlanc was viewed as having been a role model for Acadians, and was complimented for having drawn the attention of the country to [[History of the Acadians|Acadian history]] and culture. As such, he was seen as a symbol for reconciliation, given the past relations between the Acadians and the [[Monarchy of the United Kingdom|Canadian Crown's predecessor]]. At the same time, LeBlanc was also credited for returning Rideau Hall to a status closer to that which it held a century previous, when it was the centre of life in the national capital.<ref name=CMNLeB />\n[[File:Flag of Canadian Governor General LeBlanc.svg|thumb|left|The [[Flag of the Governor General of Canada|Governor General's standard]] as redesigned at LeBlanc's direction, declawed and delangued]]\n\nAlthough LeBlanc enjoyed all the provinces and territories, his visits touching small towns as well as big cities, he travelled to events in his home province to a degree that some saw as disproportionate. Moreover, LeBlanc never sought media coverage, with the result that many Canadians were unaware of who he was, and his down-to-earth demeanour was thought by some to have been too \"folksy\" for the post.<ref name=CMNSun /> The accusations of political patronage also failed to evaporate during LeBlanc's governorship; while LeBlanc was viceroy, his son, [[Dominic LeBlanc|Dominic]], continued to work for the prime minister's office until 1997, when he ran for election to the House of Commons in LeBlanc's old riding, where the Governor General had a series of events planned the very week he dropped the [[Writ of election|election writs]]. Further, LeBlanc's daughter maintained employment as a political assistant to Liberal Cabinet ministers, and some of the Governor General's staff had close Liberal Party connections.<ref name=CMNLeB />\n\nPersonal touches were also left on [[Flag of the Governor General of Canada|the symbol of the Canadian viceregal office]], from which LeBlanc removed the claws and tongue of the crowned lion,<ref name=CMNSun /> saying that they were impolite and un-Canadian. Though the change did not gather much attention until near the end of LeBlanc's tenure, the reaction, when it came, was generally unfavourable, and the modifications were undone by his successor.<ref name=CMNLeB />\n\n==Post-viceregal life and death==\n[[File:StJosephMemramcook.jpg|thumb|St. Thomas Church in Memramcook was the location of his [[State funerals in Canada|state funeral]].]]After being released from the Queen's service, LeBlanc returned to New Brunswick. There, after a lengthy battle with [[Alzheimer's disease]], he died on June 24, 2009, in [[Grande-Digue, New Brunswick|Grande-Digue]].<ref>{{Citation|last=Taber|first=Jane|title=Rom\u00e9o LeBlanc dies at 81|newspaper=The Globe and Mail|date=June 24, 2009|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/romeo-leblanc-dies-at-81/article1195318|accessdate=June 26, 2009}}</ref>\n\nHe was, as is protocol for all incumbent and former governors general, accorded a [[State funerals in Canada|state funeral]], which took place on July 3 of the same year, in Memramcook. The casket's path through the community was lined with officers from the [[Fisheries and Oceans Canada|Department of Fisheries and Oceans]], paying homage to LeBlanc's time as [[minister of the Crown]] with that portfolio,<ref>{{Citation|last=Canadian Press|title='Great gentleman of Acadia' honoured| newspaper=Toronto Star|date=July 3, 2009|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/article/660377|accessdate=July 3, 2009}}</ref> and the sitting governor general, [[Micha\u00eblle Jean]], her prime minister, [[Stephen Harper]], and LeBlanc's former prime minister, Jean Chr\u00e9tien, all attended.<ref>{{Citation|last=Moore|first=Oliver|title=Dignitaries gather to mourn LeBlanc|newspaper=The Globe and Mail| date=July 3, 2009|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/dignitaries-gather-to-mourn-leblanc/article1205295|accessdate=July 3, 2009}}</ref>\n\n[[Canada Post stamp releases (2010-2014)|Canada Post]] featured LeBlanc on a postage stamp released on February 8, 2010.<ref>Canada Post ''Details'', January to March 2010, Volume XIX, No. 1, pp. 24\u201325</ref>\n\n==Titles, styles, honours, and arms==\n\n===Titles===\n{{Infobox viceroy styles\n| image    = [[File:Badge of the Governor-General of Canada.svg|50px]]\n| name     = Rom\u00e9o LeBlanc<br />(1995\u20131999)\n| dipstyle = His Excellency the Right Honourable<br />''Son Excellence le tr\u00e8s honorable''\n| offstyle = Your Excellency<br />''Votre Excellence''\n| altstyle = Sir<br />''Monsieur''\n}}\n\n* '''August 8, 1974{{spaced ndash}}February 8, 1995''': ''The Honourable'' Rom\u00e9o LeBlanc\n* '''February 8, 1995{{spaced ndash}}October 7, 1999''': ''His Excellency the Right Honourable'' Rom\u00e9o LeBlanc, Governor General and Commander-in-Chief in and over Canada\n* '''October 7, 1999{{spaced ndash}}June 24, 2009''': ''The Right Honourable'' Rom\u00e9o LeBlanc\n\n===Honours===\n{| border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"2\" cellspacing=\"0\"  style=\"margin:auto; margin:1em 1em 1em 0; background:white; border:1px #0047ab solid; border-collapse:collapse;\"\n|- style=\"background:white;\"\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|<span style=\"color:black;\">Ribbon bars of Rom\u00e9o LeBlanc</span>\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|ribbon=Order of Canada (CC) ribbon bar.png}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|ribbon=Order of Military Merit (Canada) ribbon (CMM).jpg}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|ribbon=VOStJ ribbon.png}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|ribbon=Order of New Brunswick ribbon.png}}\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|ribbon=Canada125 ribbon.png}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|ribbon=QEII Golden Jubilee Medal ribbon.png}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|ribbon=CD-ribbon.png}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|ribbon=National Order of Merit Grand Officer ribbon.png}}\n|}\n\n;Appointments\n* {{flagicon|Canada}} '''January 4, 1973{{spaced ndash}}July 9, 1984''': [[Member of Parliament#Canada|Member of Parliament]] (MP)\n* {{flagicon|Canada}} '''August 8, 1974{{spaced ndash}}June 24, 2009''': [[Queen's Privy Council for Canada|Member of the Queen's Privy Council for Canada]] (PC)\n* {{flagicon|Canada}} '''February 8, 1995{{spaced ndash}}October 8, 1999''': [[Order of Canada|Chancellor and Principal Companion of the Order of Canada]] (CC)<ref>{{Citation|url=http://archive.gg.ca/honours/nat-ord/oc/index_e.asp|last=Office of the Governor General of Canada|authorlink=Governor General of Canada|title=Honours> Order of Canada> Search: Order of Canada Membership List > LeBlanc, Raymond P. > Raymond P. LeBlanc, C.M., M.D., F.R.C.S.C.|publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=February 27, 2009}}</ref>\n** '''October 8, 1999{{spaced ndash}}June 24, 2009''': Companion of the Order of Canada (CC)\n* {{flagicon|Canada}} '''February 8, 1995{{spaced ndash}}October 8, 1999''': [[Order of Military Merit (Canada)|Chancellor and Commander of the Order of Military Merit]] (CMM)\n** '''October 8, 1999{{spaced ndash}}June 24, 2009''': Commander of the Order of Military Merit (CMM)\n* {{flagicon|Canada}} '''February 8, 1995{{spaced ndash}}October 8, 1999''': [[Venerable Order of Saint John|Knight of Justice, Prior, and Chief Officer in Canada of the Most Venerable Order of the Hospital of Saint John of Jerusalem]] (KStJ)<ref>{{Citation|url=http://archive.gg.ca/gg/rr/ins/index_e.asp|last=Office of the Governor General of Canada|title=Governor General > Role and Responsibilities> Insignia Worn by the Governor General|publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada|accessdate=February 3, 2010}}</ref>\n** '''October 8, 1999{{spaced ndash}}June 24, 2009''': Knight of Justice of the Most Venerable Order of the Hospital of Saint John of Jerusalem (KStJ)\n[[File:Parc Leblanc.jpg|thumb|right|LeBlanc Park in LeBlanc's hometown of [[Memramcook, New Brunswick]]]]\n* {{flagicon|Canada}} '''February 8, 1995{{spaced ndash}}October 8, 1999''': [[Scouts Canada#Organizational Structure|Chief Scout of Canada]]\n* {{flagicon|Canada}} '''1995{{spaced ndash}}June 24, 2009''': [[Royal Military College of Canada|Honorary Member of the Royal Military College of Canada Club]]\n* {{flagicon|New Brunswick}} '''August 1, 2005{{spaced ndash}}June 24, 2009''': [[Order of New Brunswick|Member of the Order of New Brunswick]] (ONB)<ref>{{cite press release|title=Order of New Brunswick recipients announced|publisher=Intergovernmental and International Relations|date=August 1, 2005|url=http://www.gnb.ca/cnb/news/iga/2005e0954ig.htm| accessdate=March 2, 2009}}</ref>\n\n;Medals\n* {{flagicon|Canada}} '''1992''': [[Commemorative Medal for the 125th Anniversary of the Confederation of Canada]]\n* {{flagicon|Canada}} '''February 8, 1995''': [[Canadian Forces Decoration]] (CD)\n* {{flagicon|Canada}} '''2002''': [[Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal]]\n\n;Foreign honours\n* {{flagicon|France}} '''2002{{spaced ndash}}June 24, 2009''': ''[[Ordre national du M\u00e9rite|Grand-officier du l'Ordre national du M\u00e9rite]]''<ref>{{Citation| title=Government House: Awards to Canadians| journal=Canada Gazette|volume=136|issue=39|publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada|location=Ottawa|date=September 28, 2002|url=http://gazette.gc.ca/archives/p1/2002/2002-09-28/html/gh-rg-eng.html| accessdate=February 3, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706181817/http://gazette.gc.ca/archives/p1/2002/2002-09-28/html/gh-rg-eng.html|archivedate=July 6, 2011}}</ref>\n\n====Honorary military appointments====\n* {{flagicon|CAN|army}} '''February 8, 1990{{spaced ndash}}October 8, 1999''': Colonel of [[the Governor General's Horse Guards]]\n* {{flagicon|CAN|army}} '''February 8, 1990{{spaced ndash}}October 8, 1999''': Colonel of the [[Governor General's Foot Guards]]\n* {{flagicon|CAN|army}} '''February 8, 1990{{spaced ndash}}October 8, 1999''': Colonel of [[the Canadian Grenadier Guards]]\n\n====Honorary degrees====\n* {{flagicon|New Brunswick}} '''1977''': [[Mount Allison University]], [[Doctor of Civil Law]] (DCL)<ref name=LAC/>\n* {{flagicon|New Brunswick}} '''1979''': [[University of Moncton]], Doctor of Public Administration (DPA)<ref name=LAC/>\n* {{flagicon|Nova Scotia}} '''1995''': [[Universit\u00e9 Sainte-Anne]], [[Doctor of Laws]] (LLD)<ref name=LAC/>\n* {{flagicon|Ontario}} '''1996''': [[Ryerson University]], [[Doctor of Letters]] (DLitt)<ref name=GGHigh/>\n* {{flagicon|Ontario}} '''1996''': [[University of Ottawa]], [[Honorary degree|Doctor of the University]] (DUniv)<ref name=GGHigh/>\n* {{flagicon|New Brunswick}} '''1997''': [[St. Thomas University (New Brunswick)|St. Thomas University]], Doctor of Laws (LLD)<ref name=GGHigh/>\n* {{flagicon|Newfoundland and Labrador}} '''1997''': [[Memorial University of Newfoundland]], Doctor of Laws (LLD)<ref name=GGHigh/>\n* {{flagicon|Quebec}} '''1997''': [[McGill University]], Doctor of Laws (LLD)<ref name=GGHigh/>\n* {{flagicon|New Brunswick}} '''1999''': [[University of New Brunswick]], Doctor of Laws (LLD)<ref name=GGHigh/>\n\n====Honorific eponyms====\n;Geographic locations\n* {{flag|New Brunswick}}: LeBlanc Park, [[Memramcook, New Brunswick|Memramcook]]\n* {{flag|New Brunswick}}: [[Greater Moncton Rom\u00e9o LeBlanc International Airport]], [[Dieppe, New Brunswick|Dieppe]]\n\n===Arms===\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|image             = File:ARMS.PNG\n|bannerimage       =\n|badgeimage        =\n|notes             = Just prior to his installation as Governor General, LeBlanc was granted a personal [[coat of arms]] that depicted his Acadian and Canadian roots.\n|year_adopted      = January 1, 1995\n|crest             = Four eagle feathers within a circlet of Micmac quill decration Gules\n|torse             =\n|helm              =\n|escutcheon        = Per pile rompu Gules and Argent, in chief a Star of Acadia all Or ensigned by a representation of the Royal Crown all Or\n|supporters        = Two dolphins Argent each gorged with a collar of maple leaves Gules and fleurs de lys Or, pendand therefrom a plate Azure, dexter surmounted by a steam locomotive wheel Or, sinister surmounted by a book Or\n|compartment       = Issuant from a mound set with maple leaves all Gules flanked by waves proper\n|motto             = '''SEMPER AMISSOS MEMINISSE DECET'''<br />''(It is right to remember the forgotten)''\n|orders            = The ribbon and insignia of a Companion of the [[Order of Canada]].<br />'''DESIDERANTES MELIOREM PATRIAM'''<br />''(They desire a better country)''\n|other_elements    =\n|banner            =\n|badge             =\n|symbolism         = The use of white recalls the LeBlanc family name, while the pile refers to the Memramcook Valley, where LeBlanc was born, and the [[dolphin]]s evoke the Rivi\u00e8re Dauphin (now [[Annapolis River]]), where LeBlanc's ancestors settled in the mid 17th century, as well as LeBlanc's maritime heritage and his service as the minister of fisheries. The star is a symbol long used by the Acadians, as are the fleurs de lys representative of LeBlanc's roots in that community, and the royal crown represents LeBlanc's appointment as the representative of the Canadian sovereign. The [[eagle]] feathers, a symbols of peace, honour the Canadian [[First Nations]], and the number represents LeBlanc's four children. More family links are depicted in the steam locomotive wheel{{spaced ndash}}representing LeBlanc's father's service on [[Rail transport in Canada|the Canadian railways]]{{spaced ndash}}and the book evoking LeBlanc's training and work as a teacher. The compartment symbolises a multi-ethnic Canada between two seas, and recalls the [[Mi'kmaq language|Micmac]] origin of the word Memramcook, meaning multi-coloured landscape.<ref>{{Citation|url=http://archive.gg.ca/heraldry/emb/05/emblems-rl_e.asp|last=Office of the Governor General of Canada|title=Heraldry> Emblems of Canada and of Government House> Symbols of Past Governors General> The Coat of Arms of The Right Honourable Rom\u00e9o LeBlanc|publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| date=October 1, 1999|accessdate=March 4, 2009}}</ref>}}\n\n==See also==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* [[List of people from Westmorland County, New Brunswick]]\n* [[Journalism]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=35em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://archive.gg.ca/gg/fgg/bios/02/index_e.asp Website of the Governor General of Canada entry for Rom\u00e9o LeBlanc]\n* [http://epe.lac-bac.gc.ca/100/200/301/ic/can_digital_collections/governor/standard/pg03a.htm Library and Archives Canada entry for Rom\u00e9o LeBlanc]\n* {{Canadian Parliament links|ID=2559}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ray Hnatyshyn]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Governor General of Canada]]|years=February 8, 1995 \u2013 October 7, 1999}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Adrienne Clarkson]]}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{Canadian federal ministry navigational box header |ministry=20}}\n{{ministry box cabinet posts\n| post5         = [[Minister of Fisheries and Oceans]]\n| post5years    = April 2, 1979{{spaced ndash}}June 3, 1979\n| post5note     =\n| post5preceded = New title\n| post5followed = [[James McGrath (Canadian politician)|James McGrath]]\n\n| post4         = [[Minister of the Environment (Canada)|Minister of the Environment]]\n| post4years    = September 14, 1976{{spaced ndash}}April 1, 1979\n| post4note     = styled as<br />Minister of Fisheries and the Environment\n| post4preceded = Himself as acting minister\n| post4followed = [[Leonard Stephen Marchand]]\n\n| post3         = [[Minister of the Environment (Canada)|Minister of the Environment]] (acting)\n| post3years    = July 1, 1976{{spaced ndash}}September 13, 1976\n| post3note     =\n| post3preceded = [[Jean Marchand]]\n| post3followed = Himself as minister\n\n| post2         = [[Minister of the Environment (Canada)|Minister of the Environment]] (acting)\n| post2years    = December 5, 1975{{spaced ndash}}January 21, 1976\n| post2note     =\n| post2preceded = [[Jeanne Sauv\u00e9]]\n| post2followed = [[Jean Marchand]]\n\n| post1         = Minister of State (Fisheries)\n| post1years    = August 8, 1974{{spaced ndash}}September 13, 1976\n| post1note     =\n| post1preceded = n/a\n| post1followed = n/a\n}}\n{{Canadian federal ministry navigational box header |ministry=22}}\n{{ministry box cabinet posts\n| post2         = [[Minister of Public Works (Canada)|Minister of Public Works]]\n| post2years    = September 30, 1982{{spaced ndash}}June 29, 1984\n| post2note     =\n| post2preceded = [[Paul James Cosgrove]]\n| post2followed = [[Charles Lapointe]]\n\n| post1         = [[Minister of Fisheries and Oceans (Canada)|Minister of Fisheries and Oceans]]\n| post1years    = March 3, 1980{{spaced ndash}}September 29, 1982\n| post1note     =\n| post1preceded = [[James McGrath (Canadian politician)|James McGrath]]\n| post1followed = [[Pierre de Ban\u00e9]]\n}}\n{{ministry box special cabinet\n| post1         = Minister responsible for the<br />[[Canada Mortgage and Housing Corporation]]\n| post1years    = September 30, 1982{{spaced ndash}}June 29, 1984\n| post1note     =\n| post1preceded = n/a\n| post1followed = n/a\n}}\n{{s-par|ca}}\n{{succession box\n| title  = [[Speaker of the Senate of Canada]]\n| years  = December 7, 1993{{spaced ndash}}November 21, 1994\n| before = [[Guy Charbonneau]]\n| after  = [[Gildas Molgat]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n| title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Beaus\u00e9jour (electoral district)|Westmorland\u2014Kent]]\n| years  = October 30, 1972 \u2013 June 29, 1984\n| before = [[Guy F. Crossman]]\n| after  = [[Fernand Robichaud]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{CanGG}}\n{{Speakers of the Canadian Senate}}\n{{CA-Ministers of Public Works}}\n{{CA-Ministers of Fisheries}}\n{{CA-Ministers of the Environment}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leblanc, Romeo}}\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:2009 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Moncton]]\n[[Category:Acadian people]]\n[[Category:Canadian male journalists]]\n[[Category:Canadian senators from New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:Deaths from Alzheimer's disease]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:Governors General of Canada]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party of Canada MPs]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party of Canada senators]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Commons of Canada from New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:Members of the Queen's Privy Council for Canada]]\n[[Category:Speakers of the Senate of Canada]]\n[[Category:St. Joseph's College alumni]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Order of Canada]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of Military Merit (Canada)]]\n[[Category:Knights of Justice of the Order of St John]]\n[[Category:Grand Officers of the National Order of Merit (France)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:Chief Scouts of Canada]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Governor General\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| honorific-suffix = {{Post-nominals|country=CAN|PC|CC|CMM|ONB|CD|size=100%}} {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|KStJ|size=100%}}\n| image            = GG-Romeo LeBlanc.jpg\n| order1           = 25th\n| office1          = Governor General of Canada\n| term_start1      = February 8, 1995\n| term_end1        = October 7, 1999\n| monarch1         = [[Elizabeth II]]\n| predecessor1     = [[Ray Hnatyshyn]]\n| successor1       = [[Adrienne Clarkson]]\n| primeminister1   = [[Jean Chr\u00e9tien]]\n| office2          = [[#External links|More...]]\n| party            = [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]]\n| birth_name       = Rom\u00e9o-Adrien LeBlanc\n| birth_date       = {{birth date|1927|12|18}}\n| birth_place      = [[Memramcook, New Brunswick|Memramcook]], [[New Brunswick]], Canada\n| death_date       = {{death date and age|2009|6|24|1927|12|18}}\n| death_place      = [[Grande-Digue, New Brunswick|Grande-Digue]], [[New Brunswick]], Canada\n| spouse           = {{unbulleted list | Lyn Carter (1966\u20131981) | [[Diana Fowler LeBlanc|Diana Fowler]] (1994\u20132009)}}\n| children         = [[Dominic LeBlanc]]<br />[[Genevieve LeBlanc]]\n| profession       = [[Politician]], [[Journalist]], [[Teacher]]\n| religion         = [[Roman Catholicism]]\n| signature        = Romeo leblanc signature.svg\n|}}\n\n'''Rom\u00e9o-Adrien LeBlanc''' {{Post-nominals|country=CAN|PC|CC|CMM|ONB|CD}} {{Post-nominals|country=GBR|KStJ}} (December 18, 1927{{spaced ndash}}June 24, 2009)<ref>{{cite web |title=State Funeral of Romeo LeBlanc |url=https://www.canada.ca/en/canadian-heritage/services/past-state-funerals-commemorations/romeo-leblanc.html |website=Government of Canada |accessdate=21 March 2019|date=2017-09-19 }}</ref> was a [[Canadians|Canadian]] journalist, politician, and statesman who served as [[Governor General of Canada]], the [[List of Governors General of Canada#Governors General of Canada, 1867\u2013present|25th]] since the [[Canadian Confederation]].\n\nLeBlanc was born and educated in [[New Brunswick]], and also studied in [[France]] prior to becoming a teacher and then a reporter for [[Radio-Canada]]. He was subsequently elected to the [[House of Commons of Canada|House of Commons]] in 1972, whereafter he served as a [[minister of the Crown]] until 1984, when he was moved to the [[Senate of Canada|Senate]] and became [[Speaker of the Senate of Canada|that chamber's Speaker]].\n\nIn 1994, he was appointed as governor general by Queen [[Elizabeth II]], on the recommendation of [[Prime Minister of Canada]] [[Jean Chr\u00e9tien]], to replace [[Ray Hnatyshyn|Ramon John Hnatyshyn]] as [[viceroy]], and he occupied the post until succeeded by [[Adrienne Clarkson]] in 1999, citing his health as the reason for his stepping down. His appointment as the Queen's representative caused some controversy, due to perceptions of political favouritism, though he was praised for raising the stature of [[Acadia]]ns and [[francophone]]s, and for returning [[Rideau Hall]] to the centre of life in Ottawa.  {{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\nOn August 8, 1974, LeBlanc was sworn into the [[Queen's Privy Council for Canada]].<ref>{{Citation|url=http://www.pco-bcp.gc.ca/index.asp?lang=eng&page=information&sub=council-conseil&doc=members-membres/chronolog-eng.htm#1971-1980|last=Privy Council Office|authorlink=Privy Council Office (Canada)|title=Information Resources> Current Chronological List of Members of the Queen's Privy Council for Canada> 1971\u20131980|publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada|date=October 30, 2008|accessdate=March 2, 2009}}</ref> He died of [[Alzheimer's disease]] on June 24, 2009, aged 81.\n\n==Youth and political career==\n[[File:1036099802 a9122606bd o.jpg|thumb|left|The rural community of [[Memramcook, New Brunswick]], where LeBlanc was born and raised]]\n\nBorn on December 18, 1927 and raised in [[Memramcook, New Brunswick]], LeBlanc obtained [[bachelor degrees]] in [[Bachelor of Arts|arts]] and [[Bachelor of Education|education]] from the [[University of St. Joseph's College|Coll\u00e8ge St-Joseph]] before studying French civilization at the [[Universit\u00e9 de Paris]]. He then moved on to teaching for nine years{{mdash}} at [[Drummond, New Brunswick|Drummond]]'s high school from 1951\u201353 and the [[New Brunswick Teachers' College]] in [[Fredericton]] from 1955-59{{mdash}} after which he obtained work between 1960-67 as a journalist with the [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]'s [[French language]] broadcaster, [[Radio-Canada]], serving in the bureaus in [[Ottawa]], the [[United Kingdom]], and the [[United States]].<ref name=LAC>{{Citation| url=http://epe.lac-bac.gc.ca/100/200/301/ic/can_digital_collections/governor/standard/pg03a.htm| last=Library and Archives Canada|title=Governor General Rom\u00e9o LeBlanc and Mrs. Diana Fowler LeBlanc|publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada|accessdate=March 2, 2009}}</ref>\n\nHis first marriage, to Joslyn \"Lyn\" Carter, with whom LeBlanc had two children (Genevieve and [[Dominic LeBlanc|Dominic]]), lasted from 1966\u201381;<ref>{{Citation|last=Martin|first=Sandra|title=He never, ever lost his roots|newspaper=The Globe and Mail|date=June 24, 2009|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/he-never-ever-lost-his-roots/article1195357|accessdate=June 24, 2009}}</ref> in 1994, he married [[Diana Fowler LeBlanc|Diana Fowler]], who also had two children from a previous marriage.<ref name=GGLeB>{{Citation|url=http://www.gg.ca/document.aspx?id=55|last=Office of the Governor General of Canada|authorlink=Governor General of Canada| title=Role and Responsibility > Former Governors General > The Right Honourable Rom\u00e9o LeBlanc|publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada|accessdate=February 1, 2010}}</ref>\n\nLeBlanc stepped into the realm of politics when he became the [[press secretary]] for successive prime ministers [[Lester B. Pearson]] and [[Pierre Trudeau]]. He then went further, winning in the [[1972 Canadian federal election|1972 federal election]] a seat in the [[House of Commons of Canada|House of Commons]] as the [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal Party]] representative for [[Beaus\u00e9jour (electoral district)|Westmorland-Kent]], paving the way for his appointment as the [[Minister of Fisheries and Oceans (Canada)|Minister of Fisheries and Oceans]] in the [[Cabinet of Canada|Cabinet]] chaired by Trudeau.\n\nLeBlanc was a key figure in Canada's imposition of a [[Exclusive Economic Zone#Canada|200-mile fishing zone]]; the establishment of a new fisheries licensing system; the widespread use of quotas and zones that protected Canadian fishermen from overexpansion and competition from [[Fishing trawler|trawlers]] owned by large companies; the owner-operator rule, requiring licence holders to operate vessels themselves; the separate-fleet rule, preventing corporations from obtaining licences for an under-65-foot fleet; and for creating an additional system of advisory committees that permitted fishermen a larger voice in fisheries management.\n\nOn one occasion, LeBlanc also persuaded Trudeau to advise the Governor General to close Canadian ports to [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] fishing vessels, a headline-grabbing diplomatic thrust that resulted in better co-operation, and forbade all foreign corporations from holding commercial fishing licences in Canada.<ref>{{Citation| last=Gough| first=Joseph| title=Managing Canada's Fisheries: From Early Days to the Year 2000| publisher=Carleton University Press| year=2007| location=Quebec| pages=289\u2013360| isbn=978-2-89448-523-1| ref=CITEREF_Gough_2007}}</ref>\n\nOn the [[Pacific Ocean|Pacific]] coast, LeBlanc oversaw the creation of the Salmonid Enhancement Program, which aimed at doubling salmon production, and quelled plans by [[Alcan]] that were deemed to threaten salmon rivers at the time.<ref>{{Harvnb| Gough| 2007| pp=368\u2013371}}</ref>\n\nLate in 1982, LeBlanc became [[Minister of Public Works (Canada)|Minister of Public Works]] for two years before being nominated by Trudeau to then Governor General [[Jeanne Sauv\u00e9]] for appointment to the [[Senate of Canada|Senate]] on June 29, 1984. He was then selected in 1993 by Prime Minister [[Jean Chr\u00e9tien]] as Governor General [[Ray Hnatyshyn]]'s appointee as [[Speaker of the Senate of Canada|that chamber's speaker]].{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\n==Governor General of Canada==\nLeBlanc's time as the Queen's viceregal representative was considered to have been low key and largely uneventful, especially in comparison to that of his successor, [[Adrienne Clarkson]].<ref name=CMNLeB>{{Citation|last=Fidelis |title=The LeBlanc Years: A Frank Assessment |journal=Canadian Monarchist News |volume=Autumn 1999 |publisher=Monarchist League of Canada |location=Toronto |year=1999 |url=http://www.monarchist.ca/cmn/1999/leblanc.htm |accessdate=March 2, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090708032551/http://www.monarchist.ca/cmn/1999/leblanc.htm |archivedate=July 8, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{Citation| last=Martin| first=Don| title=Jean is now least boring G-Gever| newspaper=National Post| date=May 28, 2009| url=https://nationalpost.com/opinion/columnists/story.html?id=f1e51d92-758b-4d2a-a554-6572d09186b1| accessdate=October 23, 2014| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://archive.is/20141023064959/http://www.nationalpost.com/opinion/columnists/story.html?id=f1e51d92-758b-4d2a-a554-6572d09186b1| archivedate=October 23, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Smith |first=David E. |year=1999 |publication-date=2007 |contribution=The Republican Option in Canada: Past and Present |editor-last=Jackson |editor-first=Michael D. |title=The Crown in Today's Federal State |periodical=Canadian Monarchist News |volume=Autumn-Winter 2007 |issue=27 |page=12 |place=Toronto-Buffalo-London |publication-place=Toronto |publisher=Monarchist League of Canada |url=http://www.monarchist.ca/cmn/2007/AutumnWinter_2007_CMN.pdf |accessdate=July 26, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090708031338/http://www.monarchist.ca/cmn/2007/AutumnWinter_2007_CMN.pdf |archivedate=July 8, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{Citation|last=Boyce |first=Peter |year=2008 |publication-date=October 2009 |contribution=The Queen's Other Realms: The Crown and its Legacy in Australia, Canada and New Zealand |isbn=978-1-86287-700-9 |editor-last=Jackson |editor-first=Michael D. |title=The Senior Realms of the Queen |periodical=Canadian Monarchist News |volume=Autumn 2009 |issue=30 |page=10 |place=Sydney |publication-place=Toronto |publisher=Monarchist League of Canada |url=http://www.monarchist.ca/cmn/2009/Autumn_2009_CMN.pdf |accessdate=October 22, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091229100400/http://www.monarchist.ca/cmn/2009/Autumn_2009_CMN.pdf |archivedate=December 29, 2009 }}</ref> He was, however, the first governor general of [[Acadia]]n heritage, which earned praise from the Acadian community, and he was also the first from the Canadian [[maritimes]] to be appointed as viceroy.<ref name=CMNLeB />\n\n===As governor general-designate===\n[[File:SandringhamHouseWestseite.jpg|thumb|right|[[Sandringham House]], where LeBlanc met with [[Monarchy of Canada|Queen]] [[Elizabeth II]] after his appointment as Governor General-Designate]]\nIt was announced from the [[Office of the Prime Minister (Canada)|Office of the Prime Minister of Canada]] on November 22, 1994 that [[Monarchy of Canada|Queen]] [[Elizabeth II]] had approved [[Prime Minister of Canada|Prime Minister]] [[Jean Chr\u00e9tien]]'s choice of LeBlanc to succeed [[Ray Hnatyshyn]] as the Queen's representative.\n\nThereafter, LeBlanc was invited to an [[Audience (meeting)|audience]] with the Queen at [[Sandringham House]], and he was said to have been impressed and inspired by the devotion to duty on the part of both Elizabeth and [[Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother|her mother]].<ref name=CMNSun>{{Citation| author=Editorial| title=No Garish Sun| journal=Canadian Monarchist News|volume=Autumn 1999|publisher=Monarchist League of Canada|url=http://www.monarchist.ca/cmn/1999/edcom2.htm|accessdate=March 7, 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090708032115/http://www.monarchist.ca/cmn/1999/edcom2.htm|archivedate=July 8, 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe commission appointing LeBlanc under the [[royal sign-manual]] and [[Great Seal of Canada]] was issued on January 16, 1995.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/databases/canada-gazette/093/001060-119.01-e.php?image_id_nbr=610383&document_id_nbr=1372&f=g&PHPSESSID=aak0t0369mpbg265s99kr6ku31|title=ARCHIVED - Item Display - A Nation's Chronicle: The Canada Gazette - Library and Archives Canada|publisher=Collectionscanada.gc.ca|accessdate=March 18, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe largest bout of publicity around LeBlanc and regarding his governor generalcy came immediately after the announcement of his appointment to the post: although previous governors general had worked as politicians prior to and after serving as viceroy, the recommendation of a prominent [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal Party]] politician and organiser was criticised as being little more than a [[patronage]] gift from the Prime Minister to a loyal party member.\n\nIn the [[1993 Canadian federal election|1993 federal election]], LeBlanc had been one of the chief architects of the Liberal Party's election strategy, and was a strong party loyalist. In protest, both [[Reform Party of Canada]] leader [[Preston Manning]] and [[Bloc Qu\u00e9b\u00e9cois]] leader [[Lucien Bouchard]] refused to attend LeBlanc's installation ceremony.<ref name=CMNLeB/>\n\n===In office===\nAs with each governor general, LeBlanc took on unofficial and personal mandates, choosing for himself: [[Volunteering|voluntarism]], the teaching of [[History of Canada|Canadian history]], [[Aboriginal peoples in Canada|Canada's Aboriginal peoples]], and the military. He spoke often about the generosity, tolerance, and compassion of Canadians, and admired the dignity and abilities of the common citizen.\n\nTo recognize the \"unsung heroes\" who volunteer their time and effort to help others, LeBlanc initiated in 1996 the [[Governor General's Caring Canadian Award]], and, on June 21, of the same year, was proud to issue a [[Proclamation|royal proclamation]] inaugurating [[National Aboriginal Day]] as an annual observance.<ref>{{Citation| url=http://archive.gg.ca/gg/fgg/bios/02/causes_e.asp| last=Office of the Governor General of Canada| authorlink=Governor General of Canada|title=Governor General > Former Governors General > Rom\u00e9o LeBlanc > Personal Causes of the Rt. Hon. Rom\u00e9o LeBlanc| publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=March 3, 2009}}</ref>\n\nAs well, in 1996 LeBlanc formed the Governor General's Award for Excellence in Teaching Canadian History, in 1999 partnered with the [[Canada Council|Canada Council for the Arts]] to create the [[Governor General's Award#Governor General's Awards in Visual and Media Arts|Governor General's Awards in Visual and Media Arts]], oversaw the issuance of the Governor General's Canadian History Medal for the Millennium, and established the Governor General's Millennium Edition of the Map of Canada, which was taken into space in 1999 by [[Julie Payette]].<ref name=GGHigh>{{Citation|url=http://archive.gg.ca/gg/fgg/bios/02/wrap-up_e.asp|last=Office of the Governor General of Canada|authorlink=Governor General of Canada|title=Governor General> Former Governors General > Rom\u00e9o LeBlanc> Highlights of the Mandate|publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada|accessdate=February 3, 2010}}</ref>\n\nLeBlanc travelled to all parts of Canada and had a special affinity for small towns and cities, making himself particularly visible in those parts of [[Quebec]] after the [[1995 Quebec independence referendum|province's referendum on secession in 1995]]. He participated in more than 2,000 events, including the annual New Year's [[Lev\u00e9e (event)|Lev\u00e9e]], which he moved to various locations around the country, seeing the party organised at [[Ottawa]], [[Ontario]], in 1996; [[Quebec City]], [[Quebec]], in 1997; [[Winnipeg]], [[Manitoba]], in 1998; and [[St. John's, Newfoundland and Labrador]], in 1999.\n\nOver the same years, LeBlanc also had public access to Rideau Hall and [[Rideau Hall#Grounds|its grounds]] expanded and improved{{mdash}} including opening a dedicated visitors' centre in 1997{{mdash}} so that the number of visitors increased threefold to approximately 125,000 people per year.<ref name=GGHigh/> In keeping with his respect for the First Peoples of Canada, LeBlanc placed a totem pole and inukshuk prominently on the royal property.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\nAmongst numerous other official and ceremonial duties, the Governor General granted [[Royal Assent]] to amendments to [[Constitution of Canada|the constitution]] on three occasions: April 21, 1997, December 19, 1997, and January 8, 1998, and also issued the royal proclamation announcing the creation of the territory of [[Nunavut]] on April 1, 1999. LeBlanc welcomed to Rideau Hall the Queen, [[Prince Philip, Duke of Edinburgh]], and [[Charles, Prince of Wales|Prince Charles, Prince of Wales]], along with a host of foreign dignitaries such as [[President of the United States|United States president]] [[Bill Clinton]] and his wife, [[Hillary Clinton|Hillary]]; [[Hussein of Jordan|King Hussein]] and [[Queen Noor of Jordan]], and later Hussein's son, [[Abdullah II of Jordan|King Abdullah II]], and his wife [[Queen Rania of Jordan|Queen Rania]]; as well as [[President of South Africa]] [[Nelson Mandela]]; and [[President of the People's Republic of China|President of China]] [[Jiang Zemin]]. Further, he undertook eight [[state visits]], becoming the first governor general of Canada to make such trips to the [[Czech Republic]], [[India]], [[Pakistan]], the [[Ivory Coast]], [[Tanzania]], [[Mali]], and [[Morocco]].<ref name=GGHigh/>\n\n===Legacy===\nAs governor general, LeBlanc was viewed as having been a role model for Acadians, and was complimented for having drawn the attention of the country to [[History of the Acadians|Acadian history]] and culture. As such, he was seen as a symbol for reconciliation, given the past relations between the Acadians and the [[Monarchy of the United Kingdom|Canadian Crown's predecessor]]. At the same time, LeBlanc was also credited for returning Rideau Hall to a status closer to that which it held a century previous, when it was the centre of life in the national capital.<ref name=CMNLeB />\n[[File:Flag of Canadian Governor General LeBlanc.svg|thumb|left|The [[Flag of the Governor General of Canada|Governor General's standard]] as redesigned at LeBlanc's direction, declawed and delangued]]\n\nAlthough LeBlanc enjoyed all the provinces and territories, his visits touching small towns as well as big cities, he travelled to events in his home province to a degree that some saw as disproportionate. Moreover, LeBlanc never sought media coverage, with the result that many Canadians were unaware of who he was, and his down-to-earth demeanour was thought by some to have been too \"folksy\" for the post.<ref name=CMNSun /> The accusations of political patronage also failed to evaporate during LeBlanc's governorship; while LeBlanc was viceroy, his son, [[Dominic LeBlanc|Dominic]], continued to work for the prime minister's office until 1997, when he ran for election to the House of Commons in LeBlanc's old riding, where the Governor General had a series of events planned the very week he dropped the [[Writ of election|election writs]]. Further, LeBlanc's daughter maintained employment as a political assistant to Liberal Cabinet ministers, and some of the Governor General's staff had close Liberal Party connections.<ref name=CMNLeB />\n\nPersonal touches were also left on [[Flag of the Governor General of Canada|the symbol of the Canadian viceregal office]], from which LeBlanc removed the claws and tongue of the crowned lion,<ref name=CMNSun /> saying that they were impolite and un-Canadian. Though the change did not gather much attention until near the end of LeBlanc's tenure, the reaction, when it came, was generally unfavourable, and the modifications were undone by his successor.<ref name=CMNLeB />\n\n==Post-viceregal life and death==\n[[File:StJosephMemramcook.jpg|thumb|St. Thomas Church in Memramcook was the location of his [[State funerals in Canada|state funeral]].]]After being released from the Queen's service, LeBlanc returned to New Brunswick. There, after a lengthy battle with [[Alzheimer's disease]], he died on June 24, 2009, in [[Grande-Digue, New Brunswick|Grande-Digue]].<ref>{{Citation|last=Taber|first=Jane|title=Rom\u00e9o LeBlanc dies at 81|newspaper=The Globe and Mail|date=June 24, 2009|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/politics/romeo-leblanc-dies-at-81/article1195318|accessdate=June 26, 2009}}</ref>\n\nHe was, as is protocol for all incumbent and former governors general, accorded a [[State funerals in Canada|state funeral]], which took place on July 3 of the same year, in Memramcook. The casket's path through the community was lined with officers from the [[Fisheries and Oceans Canada|Department of Fisheries and Oceans]], paying homage to LeBlanc's time as [[minister of the Crown]] with that portfolio,<ref>{{Citation|last=Canadian Press|title='Great gentleman of Acadia' honoured| newspaper=Toronto Star|date=July 3, 2009|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/article/660377|accessdate=July 3, 2009}}</ref> and the sitting governor general, [[Micha\u00eblle Jean]], her prime minister, [[Stephen Harper]], and LeBlanc's former prime minister, Jean Chr\u00e9tien, all attended.<ref>{{Citation|last=Moore|first=Oliver|title=Dignitaries gather to mourn LeBlanc|newspaper=The Globe and Mail| date=July 3, 2009|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/news/national/dignitaries-gather-to-mourn-leblanc/article1205295|accessdate=July 3, 2009}}</ref>\n\n[[Canada Post stamp releases (2010-2014)|Canada Post]] featured LeBlanc on a Canadian postage stamp released on February 8, 2010.<ref>Canada Post ''Details'', January to March 2010, Volume XIX, No. 1, pp. 24\u201325</ref>\n\n==Titles, styles, honours, and arms==\n\n===Titles===\n{{Infobox viceroy styles\n| image    = [[File:Badge of the Governor-General of Canada.svg|50px]]\n| name     = Rom\u00e9o LeBlanc<br />(1995\u20131999)\n| dipstyle = His Excellency the Right Honourable<br />''Son Excellence le tr\u00e8s honorable''\n| offstyle = Your Excellency<br />''Votre Excellence''\n| altstyle = Sir<br />''Monsieur''\n}}\n\n* '''August 8, 1974{{spaced ndash}}February 8, 1995''': ''The Honourable'' Rom\u00e9o LeBlanc\n* '''February 8, 1995{{spaced ndash}}October 7, 1999''': ''His Excellency the Right Honourable'' Rom\u00e9o LeBlanc, Governor General and Commander-in-Chief in and over Canada\n* '''October 7, 1999{{spaced ndash}}June 24, 2009''': ''The Right Honourable'' Rom\u00e9o LeBlanc\n\n===Honours===\n{| border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"2\" cellspacing=\"0\"  style=\"margin:auto; margin:1em 1em 1em 0; background:white; border:1px #0047ab solid; border-collapse:collapse;\"\n|- style=\"background:white;\"\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center;\"|<span style=\"color:black;\">Ribbon bars of Rom\u00e9o LeBlanc</span>\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|ribbon=Order of Canada (CC) ribbon bar.png}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|ribbon=Order of Military Merit (Canada) ribbon (CMM).jpg}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|ribbon=VOStJ ribbon.png}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|ribbon=Order of New Brunswick ribbon.png}}\n|-\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|ribbon=Canada125 ribbon.png}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|ribbon=QEII Golden Jubilee Medal ribbon.png}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|ribbon=CD-ribbon.png}}\n|{{ribbon devices|number=0|ribbon=National Order of Merit Grand Officer ribbon.png}}\n|}\n\n;Appointments\n* {{flagicon|Canada}} '''January 4, 1973{{spaced ndash}}July 9, 1984''': [[Member of Parliament#Canada|Member of Parliament]] (MP)\n* {{flagicon|Canada}} '''August 8, 1974{{spaced ndash}}June 24, 2009''': [[Queen's Privy Council for Canada|Member of the Queen's Privy Council for Canada]] (PC)\n* {{flagicon|Canada}} '''February 8, 1995{{spaced ndash}}October 8, 1999''': [[Order of Canada|Chancellor and Principal Companion of the Order of Canada]] (CC)<ref>{{Citation|url=http://archive.gg.ca/honours/nat-ord/oc/index_e.asp|last=Office of the Governor General of Canada|authorlink=Governor General of Canada|title=Honours> Order of Canada> Search: Order of Canada Membership List > LeBlanc, Raymond P. > Raymond P. LeBlanc, C.M., M.D., F.R.C.S.C.|publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| accessdate=February 27, 2009}}</ref>\n** '''October 8, 1999{{spaced ndash}}June 24, 2009''': Companion of the Order of Canada (CC)\n* {{flagicon|Canada}} '''February 8, 1995{{spaced ndash}}October 8, 1999''': [[Order of Military Merit (Canada)|Chancellor and Commander of the Order of Military Merit]] (CMM)\n** '''October 8, 1999{{spaced ndash}}June 24, 2009''': Commander of the Order of Military Merit (CMM)\n* {{flagicon|Canada}} '''February 8, 1995{{spaced ndash}}October 8, 1999''': [[Venerable Order of Saint John|Knight of Justice, Prior, and Chief Officer in Canada of the Most Venerable Order of the Hospital of Saint John of Jerusalem]] (KStJ)<ref>{{Citation|url=http://archive.gg.ca/gg/rr/ins/index_e.asp|last=Office of the Governor General of Canada|title=Governor General > Role and Responsibilities> Insignia Worn by the Governor General|publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada|accessdate=February 3, 2010}}</ref>\n** '''October 8, 1999{{spaced ndash}}June 24, 2009''': Knight of Justice of the Most Venerable Order of the Hospital of Saint John of Jerusalem (KStJ)\n[[File:Parc Leblanc.jpg|thumb|right|LeBlanc Park in LeBlanc's hometown of [[Memramcook, New Brunswick]]]]\n* {{flagicon|Canada}} '''February 8, 1995{{spaced ndash}}October 8, 1999''': [[Scouts Canada#Organizational Structure|Chief Scout of Canada]]\n* {{flagicon|Canada}} '''1995{{spaced ndash}}June 24, 2009''': [[Royal Military College of Canada|Honorary Member of the Royal Military College of Canada Club]]\n* {{flagicon|New Brunswick}} '''August 1, 2005{{spaced ndash}}June 24, 2009''': [[Order of New Brunswick|Member of the Order of New Brunswick]] (ONB)<ref>{{cite press release|title=Order of New Brunswick recipients announced|publisher=Intergovernmental and International Relations|date=August 1, 2005|url=http://www.gnb.ca/cnb/news/iga/2005e0954ig.htm| accessdate=March 2, 2009}}</ref>\n\n;Medals\n* {{flagicon|Canada}} '''1992''': [[Commemorative Medal for the 125th Anniversary of the Confederation of Canada]]\n* {{flagicon|Canada}} '''February 8, 1995''': [[Canadian Forces Decoration]] (CD)\n* {{flagicon|Canada}} '''2002''': [[Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal]]\n\n;Foreign honours\n* {{flagicon|France}} '''2002{{spaced ndash}}June 24, 2009''': ''[[Ordre national du M\u00e9rite|Grand-officier du l'Ordre national du M\u00e9rite]]''<ref>{{Citation| title=Government House: Awards to Canadians| journal=Canada Gazette|volume=136|issue=39|publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada|location=Ottawa|date=September 28, 2002|url=http://gazette.gc.ca/archives/p1/2002/2002-09-28/html/gh-rg-eng.html| accessdate=February 3, 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110706181817/http://gazette.gc.ca/archives/p1/2002/2002-09-28/html/gh-rg-eng.html|archivedate=July 6, 2011}}</ref>\n\n====Honorary military appointments====\n* {{flagicon|CAN|army}} '''February 8, 1990{{spaced ndash}}October 8, 1999''': Colonel of [[the Governor General's Horse Guards]]\n* {{flagicon|CAN|army}} '''February 8, 1990{{spaced ndash}}October 8, 1999''': Colonel of the [[Governor General's Foot Guards]]\n* {{flagicon|CAN|army}} '''February 8, 1990{{spaced ndash}}October 8, 1999''': Colonel of [[the Canadian Grenadier Guards]]\n\n====Honorary degrees====\n* {{flagicon|New Brunswick}} '''1977''': [[Mount Allison University]], [[Doctor of Civil Law]] (DCL)<ref name=LAC/>\n* {{flagicon|New Brunswick}} '''1979''': [[University of Moncton]], Doctor of Public Administration (DPA)<ref name=LAC/>\n* {{flagicon|Nova Scotia}} '''1995''': [[Universit\u00e9 Sainte-Anne]], [[Doctor of Laws]] (LLD)<ref name=LAC/>\n* {{flagicon|Ontario}} '''1996''': [[Ryerson University]], [[Doctor of Letters]] (DLitt)<ref name=GGHigh/>\n* {{flagicon|Ontario}} '''1996''': [[University of Ottawa]], [[Honorary degree|Doctor of the University]] (DUniv)<ref name=GGHigh/>\n* {{flagicon|New Brunswick}} '''1997''': [[St. Thomas University (New Brunswick)|St. Thomas University]], Doctor of Laws (LLD)<ref name=GGHigh/>\n* {{flagicon|Newfoundland and Labrador}} '''1997''': [[Memorial University of Newfoundland]], Doctor of Laws (LLD)<ref name=GGHigh/>\n* {{flagicon|Quebec}} '''1997''': [[McGill University]], Doctor of Laws (LLD)<ref name=GGHigh/>\n* {{flagicon|New Brunswick}} '''1999''': [[University of New Brunswick]], Doctor of Laws (LLD)<ref name=GGHigh/>\n\n====Honorific eponyms====\n;Geographic locations\n* {{flag|New Brunswick}}: LeBlanc Park, [[Memramcook, New Brunswick|Memramcook]]\n* {{flag|New Brunswick}}: [[Greater Moncton Rom\u00e9o LeBlanc International Airport]], [[Dieppe, New Brunswick|Dieppe]]\n\n===Arms===\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|image             = File:ARMS.PNG\n|bannerimage       =\n|badgeimage        =\n|notes             = Just prior to his installation as Governor General, LeBlanc was granted a personal [[coat of arms]] that depicted his Acadian and Canadian roots.\n|year_adopted      = January 1, 1995\n|crest             = Four eagle feathers within a circlet of Micmac quill decration Gules\n|torse             =\n|helm              =\n|escutcheon        = Per pile rompu Gules and Argent, in chief a Star of Acadia all Or ensigned by a representation of the Royal Crown all Or\n|supporters        = Two dolphins Argent each gorged with a collar of maple leaves Gules and fleurs de lys Or, pendand therefrom a plate Azure, dexter surmounted by a steam locomotive wheel Or, sinister surmounted by a book Or\n|compartment       = Issuant from a mound set with maple leaves all Gules flanked by waves proper\n|motto             = '''SEMPER AMISSOS MEMINISSE DECET'''<br />''(It is right to remember the forgotten)''\n|orders            = The ribbon and insignia of a Companion of the [[Order of Canada]].<br />'''DESIDERANTES MELIOREM PATRIAM'''<br />''(They desire a better country)''\n|other_elements    =\n|banner            =\n|badge             =\n|symbolism         = The use of white recalls the LeBlanc family name, while the pile refers to the Memramcook Valley, where LeBlanc was born, and the [[dolphin]]s evoke the Rivi\u00e8re Dauphin (now [[Annapolis River]]), where LeBlanc's ancestors settled in the mid 17th century, as well as LeBlanc's maritime heritage and his service as the minister of fisheries. The star is a symbol long used by the Acadians, as are the fleurs de lys representative of LeBlanc's roots in that community, and the royal crown represents LeBlanc's appointment as the representative of the Canadian sovereign. The [[eagle]] feathers, a symbols of peace, honour the Canadian [[First Nations]], and the number represents LeBlanc's four children. More family links are depicted in the steam locomotive wheel{{spaced ndash}}representing LeBlanc's father's service on [[Rail transport in Canada|the Canadian railways]]{{spaced ndash}}and the book evoking LeBlanc's training and work as a teacher. The compartment symbolises a multi-ethnic Canada between two seas, and recalls the [[Mi'kmaq language|Micmac]] origin of the word Memramcook, meaning multi-coloured landscape.<ref>{{Citation|url=http://archive.gg.ca/heraldry/emb/05/emblems-rl_e.asp|last=Office of the Governor General of Canada|title=Heraldry> Emblems of Canada and of Government House> Symbols of Past Governors General> The Coat of Arms of The Right Honourable Rom\u00e9o LeBlanc|publisher=Queen's Printer for Canada| date=October 1, 1999|accessdate=March 4, 2009}}</ref>}}\n\n==See also==\n{{wikiquote}}\n* [[List of people from Westmorland County, New Brunswick]]\n* [[Journalism]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=35em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://archive.gg.ca/gg/fgg/bios/02/index_e.asp Website of the Governor General of Canada entry for Rom\u00e9o LeBlanc]\n* [http://epe.lac-bac.gc.ca/100/200/301/ic/can_digital_collections/governor/standard/pg03a.htm Library and Archives Canada entry for Rom\u00e9o LeBlanc]\n* {{Canadian Parliament links|ID=2559}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-gov}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ray Hnatyshyn]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Governor General of Canada]]|years=February 8, 1995 \u2013 October 7, 1999}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Adrienne Clarkson]]}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{Canadian federal ministry navigational box header |ministry=20}}\n{{ministry box cabinet posts\n| post5         = [[Minister of Fisheries and Oceans]]\n| post5years    = April 2, 1979{{spaced ndash}}June 3, 1979\n| post5note     =\n| post5preceded = New title\n| post5followed = [[James McGrath (Canadian politician)|James McGrath]]\n\n| post4         = [[Minister of the Environment (Canada)|Minister of the Environment]]\n| post4years    = September 14, 1976{{spaced ndash}}April 1, 1979\n| post4note     = styled as<br />Minister of Fisheries and the Environment\n| post4preceded = Himself as acting minister\n| post4followed = [[Leonard Stephen Marchand]]\n\n| post3         = [[Minister of the Environment (Canada)|Minister of the Environment]] (acting)\n| post3years    = July 1, 1976{{spaced ndash}}September 13, 1976\n| post3note     =\n| post3preceded = [[Jean Marchand]]\n| post3followed = Himself as minister\n\n| post2         = [[Minister of the Environment (Canada)|Minister of the Environment]] (acting)\n| post2years    = December 5, 1975{{spaced ndash}}January 21, 1976\n| post2note     =\n| post2preceded = [[Jeanne Sauv\u00e9]]\n| post2followed = [[Jean Marchand]]\n\n| post1         = Minister of State (Fisheries)\n| post1years    = August 8, 1974{{spaced ndash}}September 13, 1976\n| post1note     =\n| post1preceded = n/a\n| post1followed = n/a\n}}\n{{Canadian federal ministry navigational box header |ministry=22}}\n{{ministry box cabinet posts\n| post2         = [[Minister of Public Works (Canada)|Minister of Public Works]]\n| post2years    = September 30, 1982{{spaced ndash}}June 29, 1984\n| post2note     =\n| post2preceded = [[Paul James Cosgrove]]\n| post2followed = [[Charles Lapointe]]\n\n| post1         = [[Minister of Fisheries and Oceans (Canada)|Minister of Fisheries and Oceans]]\n| post1years    = March 3, 1980{{spaced ndash}}September 29, 1982\n| post1note     =\n| post1preceded = [[James McGrath (Canadian politician)|James McGrath]]\n| post1followed = [[Pierre de Ban\u00e9]]\n}}\n{{ministry box special cabinet\n| post1         = Minister responsible for the<br />[[Canada Mortgage and Housing Corporation]]\n| post1years    = September 30, 1982{{spaced ndash}}June 29, 1984\n| post1note     =\n| post1preceded = n/a\n| post1followed = n/a\n}}\n{{s-par|ca}}\n{{succession box\n| title  = [[Speaker of the Senate of Canada]]\n| years  = December 7, 1993{{spaced ndash}}November 21, 1994\n| before = [[Guy Charbonneau]]\n| after  = [[Gildas Molgat]]\n}}\n{{succession box\n| title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Beaus\u00e9jour (electoral district)|Westmorland\u2014Kent]]\n| years  = October 30, 1972 \u2013 June 29, 1984\n| before = [[Guy F. Crossman]]\n| after  = [[Fernand Robichaud]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{CanGG}}\n{{Speakers of the Canadian Senate}}\n{{CA-Ministers of Public Works}}\n{{CA-Ministers of Fisheries}}\n{{CA-Ministers of the Environment}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Leblanc, Romeo}}\n[[Category:1927 births]]\n[[Category:2009 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Moncton]]\n[[Category:Acadian people]]\n[[Category:Canadian male journalists]]\n[[Category:Canadian senators from New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:Deaths from Alzheimer's disease]]\n[[Category:Disease-related deaths in New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:Governors General of Canada]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party of Canada MPs]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party of Canada senators]]\n[[Category:Members of the House of Commons of Canada from New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:Members of the Queen's Privy Council for Canada]]\n[[Category:Speakers of the Senate of Canada]]\n[[Category:St. Joseph's College alumni]]\n[[Category:Companions of the Order of Canada]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of Military Merit (Canada)]]\n[[Category:Knights of Justice of the Order of St John]]\n[[Category:Grand Officers of the National Order of Merit (France)]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of New Brunswick]]\n[[Category:Chief Scouts of Canada]]\n", "name_user": "Yoho2001", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePost-viceregal life and death", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rom%C3%A9o_LeBlanc"}
{"title_page": "Morphine (band)", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=March 2008}}\n{{Infobox musical artist  <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Morphine\n| image                 = Mark_Sandman_Mississippi_Nights_1997.04.09.jpg\n| caption            = Morphine in 1997 at Mississippi Nights, St Louis, MO\n| image_size            =\n| background          = group_or_band\n| alias               =\n| origin              = [[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge]], [[Massachusetts]], [[United States]]\n| genre               = [[Alternative rock]], [[jazz-rock]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.salon.com/1999/07/21/sandman/ |title=Exit the Sandman |last=Smith |first=Larry |date=July 21, 1999 |publisher= Salon }}</ref> [[blues rock]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/morphine-mn0000601430/biography |title=Morphine|publisher=Allmusic }}</ref>\n| years_active        = 1989\u20131999\n| label               = [[Rykodisc]], [[DreamWorks Records|DreamWorks]]\n| associated_acts     = [[Treat Her Right]], [[Twinemen]], Orchestra Morphine, Bourbon Princess, [[Vapors of Morphine]]\n| website             =\n| past_members        = [[Mark Sandman]]<br/>[[Dana Colley]]<br/>[[Jerome Deupree]]<br/>[[Billy Conway (drummer)|Billy Conway]]\n}}\n\n'''Morphine''' was an [[United States|American]] [[alternative rock]] group formed by [[Mark Sandman]], [[Dana Colley]], and [[Jerome Deupree]] in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge]], [[Massachusetts]] in 1989.  After five successful albums and extensive touring, they disbanded after lead vocalist Sandman died of a [[myocardial infarction|heart attack]] onstage in [[Palestrina]], Italy, on July 3, 1999. Founding members have reformed into the band [[Vapors of Morphine]], maintaining much of the original style and sound.\n\nMorphine combined [[blues]] and [[jazz]] elements with more traditional [[rock music|rock]] arrangements, giving the band an unusual sound. Sandman sang distinctively in a \"deep, laid-back [[croon]]\",<ref>{{cite news | title = Morphine's addictive music is seducing a phalanx of fans | author = Matt Ashare | url = http://www.bostonphoenix.com/archive/music/99/07/08/ASHARE_MAY_94.html | newspaper = [[The Boston Phoenix]] | date = 1994-05-27 | accessdate = 2008-03-29 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080515132754/http://www.bostonphoenix.com/archive/music/99/07/08/ASHARE_MAY_94.html | archivedate = 2008-05-15 }}</ref> and his songwriting featured a prominent [[Beat generation|beat]] influence. The band themselves coined the label \"low rock\" to describe their music, which involved \"a minimalist, low-end sound that could have easily become a gimmick: a '[[power trio]]' not built around the sound of an [[electric guitar]]. Instead, Morphine expanded its offbeat vocabulary on each album.\"<ref>{{cite web | title = Morphine discography | author = Greg Kot | url = http://www.trouserpress.com/entry.php?a=morphine | publisher = TrouserPress.com | date =  | accessdate = 2008-03-30}}</ref>\n\nThe band enjoyed positive critical appraisal, but met with mixed results commercially.  In the United States the band was embraced and promoted by the [[indie rock]] community, including [[National Public Radio|public]] and [[campus radio|college]] radio stations and [[MTV]]'s ''[[120 Minutes]]'', which the band once guest-hosted, but received little support from commercial rock radio and other music television programs. This limited their mainstream exposure and support in their home country, while internationally they enjoyed high-profile success, especially in [[Belgium]], [[Portugal]], [[France]] and [[Australia]].\n\n==History==\n===Formation, independent years (1989\u20131996)===\nMorphine was formed in 1989 by bassist and vocalist Mark Sandman, a member of the bluesy alternative rock band [[Treat Her Right]], saxophonist Dana Colley, a former member of the local Boston group Three Colors, and drummer Jerome Deupree, who had played with Sandman in the Hypnosonics.  Sandman, a prolific musician who frequently experimented with home-made instruments, played a single-stringed bass guitar of his own devising with a [[slide guitar|slide]], although he later added a second string.  Deupree briefly left the group for health reasons in 1991 and was temporarily replaced by Treat Her Right drummer [[Billy Conway (drummer)|Billy Conway]].<ref name=\"Larkin\">{{cite book|title=[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music|The Virgin Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]|editor=[[Colin Larkin (writer)|Colin Larkin]]|publisher=[[Virgin Books]]|date=1997|edition=Concise|isbn=1-85227-745-9|page=873}}</ref>  These years found the group building a strong local audience and touring occasionally.\n\nWith Deupree returning, they recorded their debut album, ''[[Good (Morphine album)|Good]]'', for the Boston-based Accurate/Distortion label in 1991.<ref name=\"Larkin\"/> The album received positive reviews and increased the band's audience. The band subsequently signed to [[Rykodisc]], who re-released ''Good'' under its own imprint.<ref name=\"The Great Rock Discography\">{{cite book| first= Martin C.| last= Strong| year= 2000| title= The Great Rock Discography| edition= 5th| publisher= Mojo Books| location= Edinburgh| page= 661| isbn= 1-84195-017-3}}</ref>\n\n''[[Cure for Pain]]'', 1993's followup,<ref name=\"Larkin\"/> increased the band's audience outside of [[New England]], and singles like \"Thursday\" and \"Buena\" picked up some college radio play.  During the recording of ''Cure for Pain'', Deupree was again replaced by Conway, although Deupree still played most of the percussion work on the album.  After the album was completed, the band toured the United States, Europe, Japan and Australia.\n\nIn 1994, the songs \"Sheila\" and \"In Spite of Me\" were prominently featured on the soundtrack of the film ''[[Spanking the Monkey]]''.  The band returned to the studio in 1995 and produced ''[[Yes (Morphine album)|Yes]]''.<ref name=\"Larkin\"/> The album featured the single \"Honey White,\" the music video for which appeared on the [[MTV]] animated series ''[[Beavis and Butt-head]]''.\n\n===DreamWorks Records years (1997\u20131999)===\nAfter two years of touring, Morphine signed with [[DreamWorks Records]], who released their major label debut, ''[[Like Swimming]]'', in 1997.<ref name=\"The Great Rock Discography\"/> It was a critical success, but did not break the band into the domestic mainstream as had been hoped. DreamWorks released a music video for the single \"Early to Bed\"; directed by [[Jamie Caliri]] and released in March 1997, the nightmarish yet humorous video became an instant favorite among fans and was later nominated for a [[Grammy awards|Grammy award]].  The band also released ''[[B-Sides and Otherwise]]'', a collection of B-sides and live recordings, on Rykodisc this same year.\n\nIn the following time, Deupree once again began performing live and in the studio with the band, making the group a four-piece.  The band's final studio album, ''[[The Night (Morphine album)|The Night]]'', was completed in early 1999.\n\nOn July 3, 1999, Sandman collapsed on the stage of the [[:it:Nel Nome del Rock|Nel Nome del Rock]] festival at the Giardini del Principe in [[Palestrina]], [[Italy]], outside of [[Rome]].<ref name=\"The Great Rock Discography\"/> He was soon pronounced dead of a heart attack and Morphine immediately disbanded. ''The Night'' was released in 2000.  Posthumous Morphine releases followed shortly thereafter, including ''[[Bootleg Detroit]]'', an \"official live bootleg\", and ''[[The Best of Morphine: 1992\u20131995]]'', both on Rykodisc.\n\n===Posthumous projects (1999\u2013present)===\n[[File:Dana Colley in BA - 2011.jpg|thumb|180px|Dana Colley performing with the posthumous Members of Morphine project in 2011]]\nWithin a year of Sandman's death, Colley and Conway created '''Orchestra Morphine''', a group of Sandman's friends and colleagues who toured to celebrate the music of the band and to raise funds for the Mark Sandman Music Education Fund. Orchestra Morphine mostly performed music from ''The Night'', but also included some other Morphine and Hypnosonics material as well.  Orchestra Morphine still performs occasionally but no longer tours.  Singer and guitarist [[Laurie Sargent]], a member of Orchestra Morphine and former vocalist for the band [[Face to Face (new wave band)|Face to Face]], later joined Colley and Conway in their first post-Morphine musical endeavor, [[Twinemen]].\n\nConway and Colley also officially formed the [[Hi-n-Dry]] [[independent record label]] and studio, converting Sandman's workspace into a commercial enterprise. The label's roster includes a number of their friends, colleagues and other Boston-area musicians.  In 2004, Hi-n-Dry released the Mark Sandman box set ''Sandbox'', which contained two CDs and a DVD of previously unreleased material spanning Sandman's musical career. The DVD featured clips from early Sandman shows, interviews from the Morphine tours, and various videos from other Sandman solo and group projects, such as Treat Her Right. However, for copyright reasons the box set did not contain any previously released material found in the Morphine catalog, Morphine videos, or promotional material produced by Rykodisc or DreamWorks Records.\n\nDeupree continued to record with various jazz musicians.  \n\nIn 2009, Colley and Deupree began regularly performing Morphine songs and new material as '''Members of Morphine''' (alternately, the Ever-Expanding Elastic Waste Band), with singer, bassist and guitarist [[Jeremy Lyons]] of [[New Orleans]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.unity.edu/NewsEvents/News/UCCPAReunion609.aspx |title=Unity.edu |publisher=Unity.edu |accessdate=2011-08-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720094425/http://www.unity.edu/NewsEvents/News/UCCPAReunion609.aspx |archivedate=2011-07-20 }}</ref>  In July 2009, the group played at Nel Nome Del Rock Festival in Palestrina, Italy, marking the ten-year anniversary of Sandman's death at the location in which it occurred.<ref>{{cite web|author=US |url=http://www.myspace.com/membersofmorphine |title=Myspace.com |publisher=Myspace.com |date= |accessdate=2011-08-07}}</ref> As of 2014, the group was renamed [[Vapors of Morphine]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.patriotledger.com/article/20140416/Entertainment/140417005 |newspaper=Patriot Ledger |author=Chad Berndtson |title=Vapors of Morphine makes it a point to keep the music fresh |accessdate=2012-12-02}}</ref> and regularly performs in Boston and New Orleans, and holds a standing weekly gig at Atwood's Tavern in Cambridge, Massachusetts.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/arts/music/2015/01/08/vapors-morphine-home-atwood-any-night/2DfssHaadUGocd8moJWJ4I/story.html|author=Sean L. Maloney |newspaper=Boston Globe |title=Vapors of Morphine at home at Atwood\u2019s|accessdate=2015-12-02}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, [[Rhino Records]] released the two-disc set ''At Your Service'', composed of unreleased Morphine material.\n\nAs of 1999, Morphine has sold over 807,000 records in the United States, according to [[Nielsen SoundScan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.hr/books?id=iggEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA11&dq=good+morphine+soundscan&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiprYa0j6PWAhVIvRoKHS5jCb0Q6AEIJzAA#v=onepage&q=good+morphine+soundscan&f=false|title=Billboard|first=Nielsen Business Media|last=Inc|date=18 December 1999|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|page=11|accessdate=14 October 2018|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n==Band members==\n*[[Mark Sandman]] \u2013 2-string slide bass, vocals, organ, tritar (3-string slide guitar), guitar, piano (1989\u20131999, died 1999)\n*[[Dana Colley]] \u2013 baritone sax, tenor sax, double sax, triangle, backing vocals (1989\u20131999)\n*[[Jerome Deupree]] \u2013 drums, percussion (1989\u20131991, 1991\u20131993, 1998\u20131999)\n*[[Billy Conway (drummer)|Billy Conway]] \u2013 drums, percussion (1991, 1993\u20131999)\n\n;Timeline\n<div style=\"text-align:left;\">\n<timeline>\nImageSize = width:850 height:150\nPlotArea = left:100 bottom:80 top:0 right:50\nAlignbars = justify\nDateFormat  = mm/dd/yyyy\nPeriod = from:01/01/1989 till:06/01/2000\nTimeAxis = orientation:horizontal format:yyyy\n\nColors =\n  id:Vocals              value:red       legend:Vocals\n  id:Saxophone           value:gray(0.5)     legend:Saxophones \n  id:Guitar              value:green       legend:Guitars\n  id:Bass                value:blue           legend:Slide_bass            \n  id:Drums               value:orange      legend:Drums,_percussion\n  id:Lines               value:black      legend:Studio_album\n  id:bars    value:gray(0.95)\n\nBackgroundColors = bars:bars\n\nLegend = orientation:vertical position:bottom columns:3\n\nScaleMajor = increment:1 start:01/01/1989\nScaleMinor = unit:year increment:1 start:01/01/1989\n\nLineData =\n\n  at:09/02/1992 color:black layer:back\n  at:09/14/1993 color:black layer:back\n  at:03/21/1995 color:black layer:back\n  at:03/11/1997 color:black layer:back\n  at:05/01/2000 color:black layer:back\n\nBarData =\n  bar:Colley text:\"Dana Colley\"\n  bar:Sandman text:\"Mark Sandman\"\n  bar:Deupree text:\"Jerome Deupree\"\n  bar:Conway text:\"Billy Conway\"\n\nPlotData=\n  width:11 textcolor:black align:left anchor:from shift:(10,-4)\n  bar:Sandman from:01/01/1989 till:07/03/1999 color:Bass\n  bar:Sandman from:01/01/1989 till:07/03/1999 color:Guitar width:7\n  bar:Sandman from:01/01/1989 till:07/03/1999 color:Vocals width:3\n  bar:Colley from:01/01/1989 till:07/03/1999 color:Saxophone\n  bar:Deupree from:01/01/1989 till:02/01/1991 color:Drums\n  bar:Deupree from:09/01/1991 till:03/01/1993 color:Drums\n  bar:Deupree from:12/01/1998 till:07/03/1999 color:Drums\n  bar:Conway from:02/01/1991 till:09/01/1991 color:Drums\n  bar:Conway from:02/01/1993 till:07/03/1999 color:Drums\n\n</timeline>\n</div>\n\n==Instruments==\n{{Unreferenced|section|date=October 2018}}\nMorphine's instrumentation was unusual for a rock band: Sandman's primary instrument was a two-string [[bass guitar]] (with the strings usually tuned to a 5th or octave interval) played with a slide; however, on the group's records he added touches of [[guitar]], [[piano]], [[electronic organ]], and other self-invented guitar instruments such as the tritar, featuring two guitar strings and one bass string. Colley played primarily [[baritone saxophone]], along with soprano or tenor saxes, and the rare [[bass saxophone]], and he sometimes played two saxes at once, a la [[Roland Kirk]]; he also played occasional [[percussion]], and [[Dobro]] on a [[A-side and B-side|B-side]].\n\n==Discography==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n;Studio albums\n* ''[[Good (Morphine album)|Good]]'' (1992)\n* ''[[Cure for Pain]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[Yes (Morphine album)|Yes]]'' (1995)\n* ''[[Like Swimming]]'' (1997)\n* ''[[The Night (Morphine album)|The Night]]'' (2000)\n\n;Live albums\n*''[[Bootleg Detroit]]'' (2000)\n\n;Compilations\n*''[[B-Sides and Otherwise]]'' (1997)\n*''[[The Best of Morphine: 1992-1995]]'' (2003)\n*''[[Sandbox: The Mark Sandman Box Set]]'' (2004)\n*''At Your Service'' (2009)\n\n{{col-2}}\n;Singles\n* \"Buena\" (1993)\n* \"Thursday\" (1993)\n* \"Sharks\" (1994)\n* \"Cure for Pain\" (1994)\n* \"Super Sex\" (1995)\n* \"Honey White\" (1995)\n* \"Early to Bed\" (1997)\n* \"[[Wild Things (film)|Murder for the Money]]\" (1997)\n* \"Eleven O'Clock\" (1999)\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.lukin.com/tos/ The Other Side]\n* [{{AllMusic|class=artist|id=p11245|pure_url=yes}} Morphine data at AllMusic]\n* [http://www.myspace.com/twinemen Twinemen on Myspace]\n\n{{Morphine}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Alternative rock groups from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:American blues rock musical groups]]\n[[Category:American experimental musical groups]]\n[[Category:Indie rock musical groups from Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Musical groups disestablished in 1999]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 1989]]\n[[Category:Musical quartets]]\n[[Category:American musical trios]]\n[[Category:Rykodisc artists]]\n[[Category:DreamWorks Records artists]]\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=March 2008}}\n{{Infobox musical artist  <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = Morphine\n| image                 = Mark_Sandman_Mississippi_Nights_1997.04.09.jpg\n| caption            = Morphine in 1997 at Mississippi Nights, St Louis, MO\n| image_size            =\n| background          = group_or_band\n| alias               =\n| origin              = [[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge]], [[Massachusetts]], [[United States]]\n| genre               = [[Alternative rock]], [[blues rock]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.salon.com/1999/07/21/sandman/ |title=Exit the Sandman |last=Smith |first=Larry |date=July 21, 1999 |publisher= Salon }}</ref> [[rock & roll]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/morphine-mn0000601430/biography |title=Morphine|publisher=Allmusic }}</ref>\n| years_active        = 1989\u20131999\n| label               = [[Rykodisc]], [[DreamWorks Records|DreamWorks]]\n| associated_acts     = [[Treat Her Right]], [[Twinemen]], Orchestra Morphine, Bourbon Princess, [[Vapors of Morphine]]\n| website             =\n| past_members        = [[Mark Sandman]]<br/>[[Dana Colley]]<br/>[[Jerome Deupree]]<br/>[[Billy Conway (drummer)|Billy Conway]]\n}}\n\n'''Morphine''' was an [[United States|American]] [[alternative rock]] group formed by [[Mark Sandman]], [[Dana Colley]], and [[Jerome Deupree]] in [[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge]], [[Massachusetts]] in 1989.  After five successful albums and extensive touring, they disbanded after lead vocalist Sandman died of a [[myocardial infarction|heart attack]] onstage in [[Palestrina]], Italy, on July 3, 1999. Founding members have reformed into the band [[Vapors of Morphine]], maintaining much of the original style and sound.\n\nMorphine combined [[blues]] and [[jazz]] elements with more traditional [[rock music|rock]] arrangements, giving the band an unusual sound. Sandman sang distinctively in a \"deep, laid-back [[croon]]\",<ref>{{cite news | title = Morphine's addictive music is seducing a phalanx of fans | author = Matt Ashare | url = http://www.bostonphoenix.com/archive/music/99/07/08/ASHARE_MAY_94.html | newspaper = [[The Boston Phoenix]] | date = 1994-05-27 | accessdate = 2008-03-29 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080515132754/http://www.bostonphoenix.com/archive/music/99/07/08/ASHARE_MAY_94.html | archivedate = 2008-05-15 }}</ref> and his songwriting featured a prominent [[Beat generation|beat]] influence. The band themselves coined the label \"low rock\" to describe their music, which involved \"a minimalist, low-end sound that could have easily become a gimmick: a '[[power trio]]' not built around the sound of an [[electric guitar]]. Instead, Morphine expanded its offbeat vocabulary on each album.\"<ref>{{cite web | title = Morphine discography | author = Greg Kot | url = http://www.trouserpress.com/entry.php?a=morphine | publisher = TrouserPress.com | date =  | accessdate = 2008-03-30}}</ref>\n\nThe band enjoyed positive critical appraisal, but met with mixed results commercially.  In the United States the band was embraced and promoted by the [[indie rock]] community, including [[National Public Radio|public]] and [[campus radio|college]] radio stations and [[MTV]]'s ''[[120 Minutes]]'', which the band once guest-hosted, but received little support from commercial rock radio and other music television programs. This limited their mainstream exposure and support in their home country, while internationally they enjoyed high-profile success, especially in [[Belgium]], [[Portugal]], [[France]] and [[Australia]].\n\n==History==\n===Formation, independent years (1989\u20131996)===\nMorphine was formed in 1989 by bassist and vocalist Mark Sandman, a member of the bluesy alternative rock band [[Treat Her Right]], saxophonist Dana Colley, a former member of the local Boston group Three Colors, and drummer Jerome Deupree, who had played with Sandman in the Hypnosonics.  Sandman, a prolific musician who frequently experimented with home-made instruments, played a single-stringed bass guitar of his own devising with a [[slide guitar|slide]], although he later added a second string.  Deupree briefly left the group for health reasons in 1991 and was temporarily replaced by Treat Her Right drummer [[Billy Conway (drummer)|Billy Conway]].<ref name=\"Larkin\">{{cite book|title=[[Encyclopedia of Popular Music|The Virgin Encyclopedia of Popular Music]]|editor=[[Colin Larkin (writer)|Colin Larkin]]|publisher=[[Virgin Books]]|date=1997|edition=Concise|isbn=1-85227-745-9|page=873}}</ref>  These years found the group building a strong local audience and touring occasionally.\n\nWith Deupree returning, they recorded their debut album, ''[[Good (Morphine album)|Good]]'', for the Boston-based Accurate/Distortion label in 1991.<ref name=\"Larkin\"/> The album received positive reviews and increased the band's audience. The band subsequently signed to [[Rykodisc]], who re-released ''Good'' under its own imprint.<ref name=\"The Great Rock Discography\">{{cite book| first= Martin C.| last= Strong| year= 2000| title= The Great Rock Discography| edition= 5th| publisher= Mojo Books| location= Edinburgh| page= 661| isbn= 1-84195-017-3}}</ref>\n\n''[[Cure for Pain]]'', 1993's followup,<ref name=\"Larkin\"/> increased the band's audience outside of [[New England]], and singles like \"Thursday\" and \"Buena\" picked up some college radio play.  During the recording of ''Cure for Pain'', Deupree was again replaced by Conway, although Deupree still played most of the percussion work on the album.  After the album was completed, the band toured the United States, Europe, Japan and Australia.\n\nIn 1994, the songs \"Sheila\" and \"In Spite of Me\" were prominently featured on the soundtrack of the film ''[[Spanking the Monkey]]''.  The band returned to the studio in 1995 and produced ''[[Yes (Morphine album)|Yes]]''.<ref name=\"Larkin\"/> The album featured the single \"Honey White,\" the music video for which appeared on the [[MTV]] animated series ''[[Beavis and Butt-head]]''.\n\n===DreamWorks Records years (1997\u20131999)===\nAfter two years of touring, Morphine signed with [[DreamWorks Records]], who released their major label debut, ''[[Like Swimming]]'', in 1997.<ref name=\"The Great Rock Discography\"/> It was a critical success, but did not break the band into the domestic mainstream as had been hoped. DreamWorks released a music video for the single \"Early to Bed\"; directed by [[Jamie Caliri]] and released in March 1997, the nightmarish yet humorous video became an instant favorite among fans and was later nominated for a [[Grammy awards|Grammy award]].  The band also released ''[[B-Sides and Otherwise]]'', a collection of B-sides and live recordings, on Rykodisc this same year.\n\nIn the following time, Deupree once again began performing live and in the studio with the band, making the group a four-piece.  The band's final studio album, ''[[The Night (Morphine album)|The Night]]'', was completed in early 1999.\n\nOn July 3, 1999, Sandman collapsed on the stage of the [[:it:Nel Nome del Rock|Nel Nome del Rock]] festival at the Giardini del Principe in [[Palestrina]], [[Italy]], outside of [[Rome]].<ref name=\"The Great Rock Discography\"/> He was soon pronounced dead of a heart attack and Morphine immediately disbanded. ''The Night'' was released in 2000.  Posthumous Morphine releases followed shortly thereafter, including ''[[Bootleg Detroit]]'', an \"official live bootleg\", and ''[[The Best of Morphine: 1992\u20131995]]'', both on Rykodisc.\n\n===Posthumous projects (1999\u2013present)===\n[[File:Dana Colley in BA - 2011.jpg|thumb|180px|Dana Colley performing with the posthumous Members of Morphine project in 2011]]\nWithin a year of Sandman's death, Colley and Conway created '''Orchestra Morphine''', a group of Sandman's friends and colleagues who toured to celebrate the music of the band and to raise funds for the Mark Sandman Music Education Fund. Orchestra Morphine mostly performed music from ''The Night'', but also included some other Morphine and Hypnosonics material as well.  Orchestra Morphine still performs occasionally but no longer tours.  Singer and guitarist [[Laurie Sargent]], a member of Orchestra Morphine and former vocalist for the band [[Face to Face (new wave band)|Face to Face]], later joined Colley and Conway in their first post-Morphine musical endeavor, [[Twinemen]].\n\nConway and Colley also officially formed the [[Hi-n-Dry]] [[independent record label]] and studio, converting Sandman's workspace into a commercial enterprise. The label's roster includes a number of their friends, colleagues and other Boston-area musicians.  In 2004, Hi-n-Dry released the Mark Sandman box set ''Sandbox'', which contained two CDs and a DVD of previously unreleased material spanning Sandman's musical career. The DVD featured clips from early Sandman shows, interviews from the Morphine tours, and various videos from other Sandman solo and group projects, such as Treat Her Right. However, for copyright reasons the box set did not contain any previously released material found in the Morphine catalog, Morphine videos, or promotional material produced by Rykodisc or DreamWorks Records.\n\nDeupree continued to record with various jazz musicians.  \n\nIn 2009, Colley and Deupree began regularly performing Morphine songs and new material as '''Members of Morphine''' (alternately, the Ever-Expanding Elastic Waste Band), with singer, bassist and guitarist [[Jeremy Lyons]] of [[New Orleans]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.unity.edu/NewsEvents/News/UCCPAReunion609.aspx |title=Unity.edu |publisher=Unity.edu |accessdate=2011-08-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720094425/http://www.unity.edu/NewsEvents/News/UCCPAReunion609.aspx |archivedate=2011-07-20 }}</ref>  In July 2009, the group played at Nel Nome Del Rock Festival in Palestrina, Italy, marking the ten-year anniversary of Sandman's death at the location in which it occurred.<ref>{{cite web|author=US |url=http://www.myspace.com/membersofmorphine |title=Myspace.com |publisher=Myspace.com |date= |accessdate=2011-08-07}}</ref> As of 2014, the group was renamed [[Vapors of Morphine]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.patriotledger.com/article/20140416/Entertainment/140417005 |newspaper=Patriot Ledger |author=Chad Berndtson |title=Vapors of Morphine makes it a point to keep the music fresh |accessdate=2012-12-02}}</ref> and regularly performs in Boston and New Orleans, and holds a standing weekly gig at Atwood's Tavern in Cambridge, Massachusetts.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/arts/music/2015/01/08/vapors-morphine-home-atwood-any-night/2DfssHaadUGocd8moJWJ4I/story.html|author=Sean L. Maloney |newspaper=Boston Globe |title=Vapors of Morphine at home at Atwood\u2019s|accessdate=2015-12-02}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, [[Rhino Records]] released the two-disc set ''At Your Service'', composed of unreleased Morphine material.\n\nAs of 1999, Morphine has sold over 807,000 records in the United States, according to [[Nielsen SoundScan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.hr/books?id=iggEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA11&dq=good+morphine+soundscan&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiprYa0j6PWAhVIvRoKHS5jCb0Q6AEIJzAA#v=onepage&q=good+morphine+soundscan&f=false|title=Billboard|first=Nielsen Business Media|last=Inc|date=18 December 1999|publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc.|page=11|accessdate=14 October 2018|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n==Band members==\n*[[Mark Sandman]] \u2013 2-string slide bass, vocals, organ, tritar (3-string slide guitar), guitar, piano (1989\u20131999, died 1999)\n*[[Dana Colley]] \u2013 baritone sax, tenor sax, double sax, triangle, backing vocals (1989\u20131999)\n*[[Jerome Deupree]] \u2013 drums, percussion (1989\u20131991, 1991\u20131993, 1998\u20131999)\n*[[Billy Conway (drummer)|Billy Conway]] \u2013 drums, percussion (1991, 1993\u20131999)\n\n;Timeline\n<div style=\"text-align:left;\">\n<timeline>\nImageSize = width:850 height:150\nPlotArea = left:100 bottom:80 top:0 right:50\nAlignbars = justify\nDateFormat  = mm/dd/yyyy\nPeriod = from:01/01/1989 till:06/01/2000\nTimeAxis = orientation:horizontal format:yyyy\n\nColors =\n  id:Vocals              value:red       legend:Vocals\n  id:Saxophone           value:gray(0.5)     legend:Saxophones \n  id:Guitar              value:green       legend:Guitars\n  id:Bass                value:blue           legend:Slide_bass            \n  id:Drums               value:orange      legend:Drums,_percussion\n  id:Lines               value:black      legend:Studio_album\n  id:bars    value:gray(0.95)\n\nBackgroundColors = bars:bars\n\nLegend = orientation:vertical position:bottom columns:3\n\nScaleMajor = increment:1 start:01/01/1989\nScaleMinor = unit:year increment:1 start:01/01/1989\n\nLineData =\n\n  at:09/02/1992 color:black layer:back\n  at:09/14/1993 color:black layer:back\n  at:03/21/1995 color:black layer:back\n  at:03/11/1997 color:black layer:back\n  at:05/01/2000 color:black layer:back\n\nBarData =\n  bar:Colley text:\"Dana Colley\"\n  bar:Sandman text:\"Mark Sandman\"\n  bar:Deupree text:\"Jerome Deupree\"\n  bar:Conway text:\"Billy Conway\"\n\nPlotData=\n  width:11 textcolor:black align:left anchor:from shift:(10,-4)\n  bar:Sandman from:01/01/1989 till:07/03/1999 color:Bass\n  bar:Sandman from:01/01/1989 till:07/03/1999 color:Guitar width:7\n  bar:Sandman from:01/01/1989 till:07/03/1999 color:Vocals width:3\n  bar:Colley from:01/01/1989 till:07/03/1999 color:Saxophone\n  bar:Deupree from:01/01/1989 till:02/01/1991 color:Drums\n  bar:Deupree from:09/01/1991 till:03/01/1993 color:Drums\n  bar:Deupree from:12/01/1998 till:07/03/1999 color:Drums\n  bar:Conway from:02/01/1991 till:09/01/1991 color:Drums\n  bar:Conway from:02/01/1993 till:07/03/1999 color:Drums\n\n</timeline>\n</div>\n\n==Instruments==\n{{Unreferenced|section|date=October 2018}}\nMorphine's instrumentation was unusual for a rock band: Sandman's primary instrument was a two-string [[bass guitar]] (with the strings usually tuned to a 5th or octave interval) played with a slide; however, on the group's records he added touches of [[guitar]], [[piano]], [[electronic organ]], and other self-invented guitar instruments such as the tritar, featuring two guitar strings and one bass string. Colley played primarily [[baritone saxophone]], along with soprano or tenor saxes, and the rare [[bass saxophone]], and he sometimes played two saxes at once, a la [[Roland Kirk]]; he also played occasional [[percussion]], and [[Dobro]] on a [[A-side and B-side|B-side]].\n\n==Discography==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n;Studio albums\n* ''[[Good (Morphine album)|Good]]'' (1992)\n* ''[[Cure for Pain]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[Yes (Morphine album)|Yes]]'' (1995)\n* ''[[Like Swimming]]'' (1997)\n* ''[[The Night (Morphine album)|The Night]]'' (2000)\n\n;Live albums\n*''[[Bootleg Detroit]]'' (2000)\n\n;Compilations\n*''[[B-Sides and Otherwise]]'' (1997)\n*''[[The Best of Morphine: 1992-1995]]'' (2003)\n*''[[Sandbox: The Mark Sandman Box Set]]'' (2004)\n*''At Your Service'' (2009)\n\n{{col-2}}\n;Singles\n* \"Buena\" (1993)\n* \"Thursday\" (1993)\n* \"Sharks\" (1994)\n* \"Cure for Pain\" (1994)\n* \"Super Sex\" (1995)\n* \"Honey White\" (1995)\n* \"Early to Bed\" (1997)\n* \"[[Wild Things (film)|Murder for the Money]]\" (1997)\n* \"Eleven O'Clock\" (1999)\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.lukin.com/tos/ The Other Side]\n* [{{AllMusic|class=artist|id=p11245|pure_url=yes}} Morphine data at AllMusic]\n* [http://www.myspace.com/twinemen Twinemen on Myspace]\n\n{{Morphine}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n[[Category:Alternative rock groups from Mass